\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0928\u093e\u091a\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092e\u0941\u0916\u094d\u092f \u092d\u093e\u0917\u093e\u0938 \u0924\u0940\u0928 \u092c\u093e\u091c\u0942\u0902\u0928\u0940 \u092a\u093e\u0923\u094d\u092f\u093e\u091a\u0940 \u0938\u0940\u092e\u093e \u0906\u0939\u0947: \u0909\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u092e\u0949\u0930\u093f\u0938 \u0915\u093e\u0932\u0935\u093e \u092c\u093f\u0917 \u092c\u0947\u0938\u093f\u0928 \u0935 \u0926\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093f\u0923\u0947\u0938 \u0935 \u092a\u0942\u0930\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0938 \u0905\u092a\u094d\u092a\u0930 \u0928\u094d\u092f\u0942\u092f\u0949\u0930\u094d\u0915 \u0916\u093e\u0921\u0940\u0926\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0930\u0947. \u0928\u094d\u092f\u0942 \u091c\u0930\u094d\u0938\u0940 \u091f\u0930\u094d\u0928\u092a\u0940\u0915 \u0928\u0947\u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0915 \u092c\u0947 \u090f\u0915\u094d\u0938\u091f\u0947\u0902\u0936\u0928 (\u0906\u092f -78) \u0924\u094d\u092f\u093e\u091a\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092a\u0936\u094d\u091a\u093f\u092e\u0947\u091a\u093e \u092a\u0930\u093f\u092e\u093f\u0924\u0940 \u091a\u093f\u0928\u094d\u0939\u093e\u0902\u0915\u093f\u0924 \u0915\u0930\u0924\u0947.\n\n<br />\n\n==Geography==\n[[Image:LSP JerseyCity.JPG|thumb|250px|Jersey City as seen from Liberty State Park|alt=|left]]\nMost of the park's area is on [[Land reclamation|landfill]] created by the [[Central Railroad of New Jersey]] (CRRNJ) and the [[Lehigh Valley Railroad]], defunct companies whose lines once terminated there. In the northeast corner of the park is the CRRNJ [[Communipaw Terminal|Terminal]], a historic transportation building. [[Statue Cruises]] offers ferries to [[Statue of Liberty National Monument, Ellis Island and Liberty Island]] that depart nearby. A {{convert|50|foot|m}} section of track from the Lehigh Valley Railroad<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/@40.7094295,-74.0473811,3a,75y,58.47h,41.02t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sakL0N8fp2nxiUdMFubkarQ!2e0!7i13312!8i6656|title=Google Maps|author=|date=|website=Google Maps|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> can be found in the park.\n\nThe southern Caven Point section of the park is separated from the main part of the park by the [[Liberty National Golf Club]] and is accessible along the water's edge using the [[Hudson River Waterfront Walkway]]. The long thin pier at the foot of Chapel Avenue that was once part of the park has been demolished. The Peninsula Park lies between the Big Basin of the [[Morris Canal]] and the Tidewater Basin in [[Paulus Hook]].  The Liberty Landing Marina is located on the Big Basin.\n\nCommunipaw Cove is part of the {{convert|36|acre|adj=on}} state [[nature preserve]] in the park and is one of the few remaining [[tidal marsh|tidal salt marshes]] along the [[New York Harbor|Hudson River estuary]]. The Interpretive Center, designed by architect [[Michael Graves]], is part of the preserve. To the west lies the Interior Natural Area, which is off limits to the public and is being allowed through natural processes to recover from environmental abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2010/11/12/nature-untamed-liberty-state-parks-interior-natural-area-continues-its-comeback/|title=Nature Untamed: Liberty State Park's Interior Natural Area Continues its Comeback|author=|date=November 12, 2010|website=JerseyCityIndependent.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> The park is also the only state park in Essex, Hudson, and Bergen counties. Another section of the park is called Liberty Industrial Park.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Ellis island air photo.jpg|thumb|View of [[Ellis Island]] and the railyards and piers of [[Central Railroad of New Jersey]] before development of the park and restoration projects|alt=|left]] Much of the park is situated on landfilled [[tidal flats]]<ref>http://www.nan.usace.army.mil/Portals/37/docs/harbor/CRP%20Planning%20Regions/PR_Upper%20Bay__8_2014.pdf</ref> that formerly supported vast [[oyster]] banks as part of the territory of the [[Hackensack Indians]], who called the area [[Communipaw]] and used it as a summer encampment. In the seventeenth century it became part of the colonial province of [[New Netherland]], the [[patroon]]ship [[Pavonia, New Netherland|Pavonia]]. The area was known as ''Jan the Lacher's Hook'', so called for the man who was the [[Homestead (buildings)|bowery's]] second superintendent, [[Jan Everts Bout]]. For many years, the village, often referred to by [[Washington Irving]], existed where the [[Liberty Science Center]] now stands. For hundreds of years it was a [[ferry]] port for local communities of [[Bergen, New Netherland|Bergen]], [[Bergen Township, New Jersey (pre-1862)|Bergen Township]], and [[Hudson County]], as well suburban and long-distance travelers to [[Manhattan]].\n\nIn the latter half of 19th century, a small island named [[Black Tom explosion#Black Tom Island|Black Tom]] was joined via landfill with the mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.state.nj.us/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty_state_park/liberty_blacktomexplosion.html|title=Liberty State Park: Black Tom Explosion|publisher=State of New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection|date=January 26, 2005|access-date=April 8, 2014}}</ref> It became a major shipping, manufacturing, and transportation hub within [[Port of New York and New Jersey]], leading to the construction of [[Communipaw Terminal]]. It was from this ferry/train station that many immigrants arriving at [[Ellis Island]] spread out across the USA. In 1916, on what is now the southeastern corner of the park, the Black Tom explosion killed as many as seven people, caused $20 million in property damage, and was felt throughout the [[Tri-State Region]].\n[[File:LibertyStatePark(pre1976).tif|thumb|left|Before opening, LSP was the site of abandoned rail facilities built on landfills]]\nConstruction of the [[North River Tunnels]], [[containerization]], and the [[Interstate Highway System]], made the area less viable. The decline of industry, deterioration of rail and maritime infrastructure, and toxic waste, eventually made the area obsolete. Abandoned buildings and [[brownfields]] dominated the landscape after the mid-twentieth century, though there was still some manufacturing and recreational use.\n\nAudrey Zapp, Theodore Conrad, Morris Pesin<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmdb.org/Marker.asp?Marker=13294|title=Morris Pesin\u2019s Legendary Canoe Trip Which Launched Liberty State Park Historical Marker|author=|date=|website=HMDb.org|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/22/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/22colnj.html?scp=39&sq=liberty+island&st=nyt | work=The New York Times | first=Kevin | last=Coyne | title=A Quest That Brought Lady Liberty Closer | date=June 22, 2008}}</ref> and [[J. Owen Grundy]] were influential environmentalists and historians who spearheaded the movement that led to the creation of Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folsp.org/grundy_editorial.htm|title=Jersey Journal FOLSP: Jersey Journal|website=FOLSP.org|access-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720184650/http://www.folsp.org/grundy_editorial.htm|archivedate=July 20, 2011}}</ref> They are remembered by the naming of places and streets along the waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1976/06/21/bicentennial-beat|title=Bicentennial Beat|first=Mark|last=Singer|date=June 14, 1976|publisher=|access-date=December 8, 2017|via=www.NewYorker.com}}</ref>\n\nIt is estimated the park suffered $20 million in damages during [[Superstorm Sandy]] in October 2012. In June 2016, the Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal reopened after a $20 million renovation to repair the extensive damage caused by Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2016/06/revamped_liberty_state_park_train_terminal_opens_p.html|title=Historic Liberty State Park train terminal reopens (Photos)|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref> As of December 2019, the Nature Interpretive Center remains closed due to storm damage. No timeline has been given for its completion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ragoza|first=Rafal|title=Latest estimates on Liberty State Park recovery from Hurricane Sandy|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=May 25, 2013|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2013/05/latest_estimates_on_liberty_st.html|accessdate=2013-05-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2015/10/2_senate_democrats_to_hold_hearing_on_future_devel.html|title=Senators want 'secret' DEP report, plan hearing on Liberty State Park's future|author=|date=October 2015|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2018, it was announced by [[New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection]] (NJDEP) that the interior {{convert|240|acre|ha|1}} of the park that have been closed off to the public for decades due to environmental contamination would be remediated into an urban marshland and forest. The restoration is to be done in phases with the initial phase focusing on a {{convert|23|acre|ha|1}} parcel of the interior. The marshland will be fed by a new channel connecting the Hudson River to the park's interior. There is currently no timeline yet for the remediation but the funding is to come from natural resource damage settlements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2018/01/nj_announces_massive_plan_to_restore_240_acres_of.html#incart_river_home|title=N.J. to turn 240 acres of Liberty State Park into wildlife oasis|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=January 11, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Points of interest==\n\n===Freedom Way and Liberty Walkway===\nA road called '''Freedom Way''' goes through the center and serves as a barrier between the area closed to the public, to its west, and the area that is open to the public, to its east. It has many [[bike path]]s, walkways, and fields.\n\n'''Liberty Walkway''', a crescent-shaped promenade, stretches from the [[Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal|CRRNJ Terminal]] along the waterfront south to the Statue of Liberty overlook, bridging two coves along the way. It is part of the longer [[Hudson River Waterfront Walkway]]. Halfway along Liberty Walkway is a bridge to [[Ellis Island]], but only authorized vehicles are allowed.\nThe southeastern corner of the park contains the Statue of Liberty overlook, picnic facilities, a playground, the ''U.S. Flag Plaza'' and ''Liberation Monument'', the Public Administration Building, and a memorial to the [[Black Tom explosion]]s. Picnicking and barbecuing facilities are also located at the southern end of the park. Originally called \"Liberty Walk\",<ref>''Landscape Architecture'' 1991 - Volume 81 Page 69  \"The first phase of the park is the {{convert|1.5|mile|km}} waterfront promenade, Liberty Walk. Construction on the promenade has already begun and will be completed in early 1991; \"</ref><ref>'' Backroads of New Jersey'' 2007 Page 48 \"Take Freedom Way south or walk the {{convert|2|mile|km}} Liberty Walk Promenade through a thirty-six-acre natural area river marsh.\"</ref><ref>Setha Low, Dana Taplin, Suzanne Scheld ''Rethinking Urban Parks: Public Space and Cultural Diversity'' 2009 p. 83 \"...Liberty State Park, includes grass-covered fields, a public boat launch, walkways along the waterfront, spacious parking lots, and ... The other connecting corridor is the {{convert|1.3|mile|km}}-long Liberty Walk, a newly built promenade along the water's edge ...\"</ref> this part of the project won a landscape award in 1995.<ref>Landscape Architecture Magazine 1995 \"Wallace Roberts & Todd (WRT) of Philadelphia and New Jersey's Department of Environmental Protection (NJDEP) were the co-winners of a Top Honor Award for the overall plan and an Honor Award for Liberty State Park and Liberty Walk \"</ref> The name \"Liberty Walk\" was already associated with Philadelphia such as through a booklet ''The Liberty Walk Through Historic Old Philadelphia'' published by the American Wax Museum, Philadelphia (before 1969) which listed a walk round 23 sites of historic interest.\n\n===Liberty Science Center===\nThe [[Liberty Science Center]], at the northwestern entrance to the park, is an interactive science museum and learning center. The center opened in 1993 as New Jersey's first major state [[science museum]]. It has science exhibits, the world's 5th largest [[IMAX Dome]] theater, the largest [[planetarium]] in the Western Hemisphere, numerous educational resources, and the original [[Hoberman sphere]], a silver, computer-driven engineering artwork designed by [[Chuck Hoberman]].<ref>[http://www.nj.gov/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty2.html NJ Department of Parks and Forests] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517032810/http://www.nj.gov/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty2.html |date=2011-05-17 }} Liberty Science Center</ref>\n\n===Monuments and memorials===\n[[File:Empty Sky P6150244.JPG|thumb|''Empty Sky'' Memorial with a remnant from the World Trade Center in the foreground]]\n''[[Liberation (Holocaust memorial)|Liberation]]'' is a 1985 bronze sculpture designed by [[Nathan Rapoport]] as a memorial to the [[Holocaust]], showing a U.S. soldier carrying out a survivor from a [[Nazism|Nazi]] death camp.<ref>[http://www.ettc.net/njarts/details.cfm?ID=424 \"Art and Architecture of New Jersey,\" ETTC.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719035536/http://www.ettc.net/njarts/details.cfm?ID=424 |date=2011-07-19 }}, retrieved May 10, 2011.</ref>\n\n''The Sail of Columbus'' is a two-story sail-shaped bronze monument designed by Gino Gianetti that commemorates the 500th anniversary of the westward journey of [[Christopher Columbus]] to America in 1492. The \"Sail\" sits atop a stone base in the shape of a ship and features scenes of Columbus and his travels.  It was dedicated from the [[Government of Italy]] and the [[Genoa|City of Genoa]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://njcu.libguides.com/jerseycitypastandpresent/libertystatepark|title=Liberty State Park|publisher=New Jersey City University|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[Empty Sky (9-11 memorial)|Empty Sky]]'' is the official state memorial to the [[September 11 attacks]] of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]]. Situated on a berm the parallel walls engraved with the names of victims are oriented to face the former [[World Trade Center site]]. Designed by architect [[Frederic Schwartz]], it was dedicated on September 10, 2011, commemorating the tenth anniversary of the attacks.<ref name=\"nj\">[http://www.state.nj.us/nj911memorial NJ 911 Memorial page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321221751/http://www.state.nj.us/nj911memorial |date=March 21, 2011 }}, retrieved February 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Friends of Liberty State Park filed a lawsuit to block the creation of the 9/11 memorial stating that New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection (DEP) did not provide enough public comment and did not authorize a proper permit linked to the project.  The Friends of Liberty State Park is led by Sam Pesin, the son of Morris Pesin, who first lobbied for the creation of Liberty State Park. Sam Pesin stated that \"The consensus [of park users] is that the memorial as proposed is a massive monstrosity that obstructs powerful views that need protection for future generations,\" he declared. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/lawsuit-against-911-memorial-prompted-threat-river-view|title=Lawsuit Against 9/11 Memorial Prompted by Threat to River View|date=2008-07-07|website=CNSNews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed commercial activities==\nThe [[Governorship of Chris Christie|administration of Governor Chris Christie]] proposed various commercial activities for the park.<ref>http://media.nj.com/hudsoncountynow_impact/other/DEP%20LSP%20report.pdf</ref> In 2017, it suggested leasing large parts of the waterfront for private marinas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2017/12/new_details_about_liberty_state_park_marina_emerge.html|title=Details emerge about new Liberty State Park marina|author=|date=December 2017|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe [[Hudson-Bergen Light Rail]] runs just west of the park with a [[Liberty State Park (HBLR station)|station]] at its entrance. Hornblower Cruises operates ferries to [[Ellis Island]] and [[Liberty Island]], and a [[Liberty Water Taxi|water taxi]] to [[Paulus Hook, Jersey City|Paulus Hook]] and the [[Battery Park City Ferry Terminal]].\n\nIn July 2012, [[North Jersey Transportation Planning Authority]] allotted $175,000 to study transportation alternatives to and within the park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2012/07/jersey_city_receives_grant_to.html|title=Jersey City receives $175,000 state grant to study public-transportation options in Liberty State Park|author=|date=July 2012|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Jersey City received a $500,000 grant to study extending Jersey Avenue from [[Downtown Jersey City|Downtown]] directly into the park, which would simplify access and create a new gateway to the park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/jjournal-news/index.ssf/2013/03/jersey_city_gets_500000_federa.html|title=Jersey City gets $500K federal grant to study extension of road into Liberty State Park|author=|date=March 2013|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> In May 2013, a new pedestrian-bike bridge was placed over Mill Creek at the small basin to replace an older one that had been destroyed by [[Superstorm Sandy]] in October 2012. It is situated so as not interfere with any new road construction.<ref>{{cite news   | last = McDonald   | first = Terrence T.   | title = Seven months after Sandy, a new $800K bridge in Jersey City   | newspaper = The Jersey Journal   | date = May 23, 2013   | url = http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2013/05/seven_months_after_sandy_a_new.html | accessdate = 2013-05-23   | quote = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mill Creek Footbridge|url=http://www.bridgesnyc.com/2013/05/mill-creek-footbridge/|website=bridgesnyc.com|accessdate=2015-01-22}}</ref> In 2014 NJDOT announced that it would build a $10 million bridge over the Morris Canal.\n<ref>{{cite news|last1=McDonald|first1=Terrence T.|title=$10M bridge connecting Downtown Jersey City to Liberty State Park closer to reality|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2014/08/bridge_connecting_downtown_jersey_city_into_liberty_state_park_closer_to_reality.html|accessdate=2015-01-22|publisher=Jersey Journal|date=August 22, 2014}}</ref> Construction of the road began in August 2019; the two-lane road bike paths.<ref>https://www.nj.com/hudson/2019/08/after-decades-of-talk-road-project-connecting-downtown-to-liberty-state-park-bergen-laf-is-underway.html</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[Image:YuvrajrDowntownJerseyCityLSP5.JPG|thumb|right|225px|Liberty Harbor]]\nThe park is featured in the video game ''[[Need for Speed: The Run]]'' towards the end of the game.\n\nIn 2002, [[Budweiser beer|Budweiser]] filmed two commercials to dedicate the [[September 11 attacks]] in the park (one in 2002, and another one in 2011). Both were only aired once<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aol.com/article/finance/2017/09/11/the-story-behind-the-911-budweiser-commercial-that-only-aired-once/23204869/|title=The true story behind the 9/11 Budweiser commercial that only aired once|last=Staff|first=A. O. L.|website=AOL.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref>\n\n===Festivals and performances===\nOn [[Labor Day]] in 1980, Republican Nominee for President [[Ronald Reagan]] kicked off his national campaign on Liberty Island, with the Statue of Liberty behind him and said: 'I want more than anything I've ever wanted, to have an administration that will, through its actions, at home and in the international arena, let millions of people know that Miss Liberty still \"Lifts her lamp beside the golden door.\"' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/9.1.80.html|title=9/1/1980 Speech|author=|date=|website=www.reagan.UTexas.edu|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 1985, [[Hall and Oates|Daryl Hall and John Oates]] played an outdoor benefit concert for the restoration of the Statue of Liberty in front of an estimated 70,000 people at Liberty State Park. The concert was later re-played on HBO.\n\n[[Liberty Weekend#July_4,_1986:_Operation_Sail,_Americana_music_concert,_and_fireworks|| Liberty Weekend]] was a concert event aired on [[ABC Network (United States)|ABC]] on Independence Day, 1984. The concert lineup included [[John Denver]], [[Whitney Houston]], and [[Johnny Cash]].\n\nIn 2000, [[Andrea Bocelli]] gave a concert at the park, broadcast on PBS, as ''American Dream&nbsp;\u2014 the Statue of Liberty concert''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocellicentralpark.com/the-worlds-most-beloved-tenor-andrea-bocelli-gifts-new-york-city-with-a-once-in-a-lifetime-musical-event|title=Universal Music Group, the world's leading music company - Home Page - UMG|author=|date=|website=UMG|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, [[Cirque du Soleil]] premiered its new work.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/13/movies/circus-review-dancing-lion-eerie-dragon-in-a-time-warp.html?scp=1&sq=Cirque%20du%20Soleil%20liberty%20State&st=cse | work=The New York Times | first=Lawrence | last=Van Gelder | title=CIRCUS REVIEW; Dancing Lion, Eerie Dragon in a Time Warp | date=April 13, 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the park began to host the Liberty [[Jazz Festival]]. This two-day event is normally held the first weekend after [[Labor Day]] each year and has included performers such as [[George Benson]], [[Waymon Tisdale]] and other jazz artists.\n\nFrom August 8\u201310, 2008, the park was the site of the [[All Points West Music & Arts Festival]]; the park hosted the festival again from July 31 to August 2, 2009, with such acts as [[Jay-Z]], [[Coldplay]], [[Tool (band)|Tool]], and [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]].\n\n===Film and TV===\n* In 1968, the film ''[[Funny Girl (film)|Funny Girl]]'' shot the \"[[Don't Rain on My Parade]]\" sequence in the Central Railroad of NJ Terminal.<ref name=\"LSP\">{{cite web|url=https://jerseydigs.com/liberty-state-park-jersey-city-history|title=Liberty State Park: New Jersey\u2019s Gift to America|website=jerseydigs.com|date=July 12, 2017|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* In 1971, the famous ''[[The Godfather]]'' (1972) scene containing [[Peter Clemenza]] and Rocco Lampone's famous exchange, \"Leave the gun. Take the cannoli\", was filmed at the site before the construction of Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoutingny.com/the-godfather-the-new-york-city-filming-locations-then-and-now/2/|title=The New York Filming Locations of The Godfather, Then and Now - Scouting NY - Page 2|author=|date=|website=www.ScoutingNY.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1997, the film ''[[Men in Black (1997 film)|Men in Black]]'' depicts a scene where [[Agent J]] delivers a newborn alien squid on Morris Pesin Drive.<ref name=\"LSP\"/>\n* In 2014, the movie, ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'', was shot at Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onthesetofnewyork.com/annie2014.html|title=Annie Film Locations|website=onthesetofnewyork.com|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*In the 2018 Netflix series ''[[Seven Seconds (TV series)|Seven Seconds]]'', the bicycle accident at the center of the plot of season 1 occurs at Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/hudson/2018/02/netflix_drama_explores_racial_tensions_police_cove.html|title=Netflix drama explores racial unrest, police cover-up in Jersey City|website=nj.com|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nSince 2007, the [[Veuve Clicquot]] Polo Classic is held every Spring at Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2018/06/veuve_clicquot_polo_classic_returns_to_liberty_sta.html|title=Veuve Clicquot Polo Classic returns to Liberty State Park with star-studded guest list (PHOTOS)|publisher=The Jersey Journal|date=June 2, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, plans were put forth outlining the use of the park as the new home of the [[United States Grand Prix|United States]] [[Formula One]] [[Grand Prix motor racing|Grand Prix]] for the [[2012 Formula One season|2012 season]].<ref>{{cite news|title=New York F1 track plans revealed&nbsp;\u2013 Jersey City bids for 2012 night race|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2010/05/04/new-york-f1-track-plans-revealed-jersey-city-bids-for-new-night-race-in-2012/|first=Keith|last=Collantine|work=F1 Fanatic|publisher=Keith Collantine|date=2010-05-04|accessdate=2010-05-04|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5w707hQJk?url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2010/05/04/new-york-f1-track-plans-revealed-jersey-city-bids-for-new-night-race-in-2012/|archive-date=2011-01-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> These plans met outrage from the community, particularly the Friends of Liberty State Park, and were ultimately rejected by the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folsp.org/preservation/grand_prix.htm|title=folsp.org|website=FOLSP.org|access-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605174724/http://www.folsp.org/preservation/grand_prix.htm|archivedate=June 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19 and 20, 2010, the park hosted the fifth round of the [[2010 Red Bull Air Race World Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2010/06/countdown_to_jersey_city_red_b.html|title=About the Red Bull Air Race in Jersey City|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=June 4, 2010|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"125\">\nFile:Lsp flag display.jpg|Twelve out of the 13 [[Flag of the United States|American Flags]] displayed at Liberty State Park (one flag not shown), with the Statue of Liberty in the background\nFile:CRRNJ Terminal, Liberty State Park, Jersey City NJ.jpg|[[Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal|Communipaw Terminal]], historic building.  Dock in foreground serves ferries to Ellis Island and Statue of Liberty\nFile:Parkflags.jpg|Flags at [[half-staff]] in Liberty State Park\nFile:Central Railroad of New Jersey Ferry Terminal.jpg|Communipaw Terminal\nFile:Twintowers1999.JPG|In 1999\nFile:Liberty State Park from One World Observatory June 2015.JPG|As seen from [[One World Trade Center]] in June 2015\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New Jersey}}\n* [[List of New Jersey state parks]]\n* [[Hudson River Waterfront Walkway]]\n* [[Hudson County, New Jersey#Parks|Hudson Parks]]\n* [[Port of New York and New Jersey]]\n* [[Marine life of New York-New Jersey Harbor Estuary]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|{{#property:Commons category}}}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.state.nj.us/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty.html}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100201224707/http://www.njcu.edu/programs/jchistory/pages/c_pages/central_Railroad_of_New_Jersey.html Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal]\n* [http://www.folsp.org Friends of Liberty State Park], an advocacy group for the park's preservation\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D05EFD6163DE633A2575BC0A9669D946296D6CF ''The New York Times''], 1913 proposal to develop Jersey City port facilities\n* {{cite report   | title = Liberty State Park Ecosystem Restoration Study   | work = Hudson-Raritan Estuary    | publisher = USACE   | date = October 2005   | url = http://www.nan.usace.army.mil/Portals/37/docs/civilworks/projects/nj/ecor/HRELiberty/realestate.pdf   | format = PDF   | accessdate =}}\n\n{{New Jersey Parks}}\n{{Hudson County Parks, New Jersey}}\n{{Nature centers in New Jersey}}\n{{Jersey City Neighborhoods}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:State parks of New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Parks in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Urban public parks]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Parks on the Hudson River]]\n[[Category:Redeveloped ports and waterfronts in the United States]]\n[[Category:Nature centers in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Geography of Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox park\n| name           = Liberty State Park\n| image          = File:Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal - 22 Sept. 2012.jpg\n| image_size     = 275\n| image_alt      =\n| image_caption  = On the Upper New York Bay at the mouth of the [[North River (Hudson River)|Hudson River]].\n| map            =\n| map_width      =\n| type           = [[Urban park]]\n| location       = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n| nearest_city   =\n| coordinates    = {{Coord|40|42|15|N|74|02|57|W|format=dms|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-NJ}}\n| area           = {{convert|1212|acre|km2}}\n| created        =\n| operator       = [[New Jersey Division of Parks and Forestry]]\n| visitation_num =\n| status         =\n| designation    =\n| open           = 1976\n| website        = {{Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Liberty State Park''' ('''LSP''') is a park in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New Jersey]], located on [[Upper New York Bay]] in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], opposite both [[Liberty Island]] and [[Ellis Island]]. The park opened in 1976 to coincide with [[United States Bicentennial|bicentennial]] celebrations<ref>{{cite web |url=http://events.norwalkcitizen-news.com/-city-nj/venues/show/10630-liberty-state-park |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120709080951/http://events.norwalkcitizen-news.com/-city-nj/venues/show/10630-liberty-state-park |archivedate=2012-07-09 }}</ref> and is operated and maintained by the [[New Jersey Division of Parks and Forestry]]. Liberty State Park covers {{convert|1212|acre|ha}}. The main part of the park is bordered by water on three sides: on the north by the [[Morris Canal]] Big Basin and on the south and east by [[Upper New York Bay]]. The [[New Jersey Turnpike#Extensions|New Jersey Turnpike Newark Bay Extension]] ([[Interstate 78 in New Jersey|I-78]]) marks its western perimeter.\n\n==Geography==\n[[Image:LSP JerseyCity.JPG|thumb|250px|Jersey City as seen from Liberty State Park|alt=|left]]\nMost of the park's area is on [[Land reclamation|landfill]] created by the [[Central Railroad of New Jersey]] (CRRNJ) and the [[Lehigh Valley Railroad]], defunct companies whose lines once terminated there. In the northeast corner of the park is the CRRNJ [[Communipaw Terminal|Terminal]], a historic transportation building. [[Statue Cruises]] offers ferries to [[Statue of Liberty National Monument, Ellis Island and Liberty Island]] that depart nearby. A {{convert|50|foot|m}} section of track from the Lehigh Valley Railroad<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/@40.7094295,-74.0473811,3a,75y,58.47h,41.02t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sakL0N8fp2nxiUdMFubkarQ!2e0!7i13312!8i6656|title=Google Maps|author=|date=|website=Google Maps|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> can be found in the park.\n\nThe southern Caven Point section of the park is separated from the main part of the park by the [[Liberty National Golf Club]] and is accessible along the water's edge using the [[Hudson River Waterfront Walkway]]. The long thin pier at the foot of Chapel Avenue that was once part of the park has been demolished. The Peninsula Park lies between the Big Basin of the [[Morris Canal]] and the Tidewater Basin in [[Paulus Hook]].  The Liberty Landing Marina is located on the Big Basin.\n\nCommunipaw Cove is part of the {{convert|36|acre|adj=on}} state [[nature preserve]] in the park and is one of the few remaining [[tidal marsh|tidal salt marshes]] along the [[New York Harbor|Hudson River estuary]]. The Interpretive Center, designed by architect [[Michael Graves]], is part of the preserve. To the west lies the Interior Natural Area, which is off limits to the public and is being allowed through natural processes to recover from environmental abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseycityindependent.com/2010/11/12/nature-untamed-liberty-state-parks-interior-natural-area-continues-its-comeback/|title=Nature Untamed: Liberty State Park's Interior Natural Area Continues its Comeback|author=|date=November 12, 2010|website=JerseyCityIndependent.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> The park is also the only state park in Essex, Hudson, and Bergen counties. Another section of the park is called Liberty Industrial Park.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Ellis island air photo.jpg|thumb|View of [[Ellis Island]] and the railyards and piers of [[Central Railroad of New Jersey]] before development of the park and restoration projects|alt=|left]] Much of the park is situated on landfilled [[tidal flats]]<ref>http://www.nan.usace.army.mil/Portals/37/docs/harbor/CRP%20Planning%20Regions/PR_Upper%20Bay__8_2014.pdf</ref> that formerly supported vast [[oyster]] banks as part of the territory of the [[Hackensack Indians]], who called the area [[Communipaw]] and used it as a summer encampment. In the seventeenth century it became part of the colonial province of [[New Netherland]], the [[patroon]]ship [[Pavonia, New Netherland|Pavonia]]. The area was known as ''Jan the Lacher's Hook'', so called for the man who was the [[Homestead (buildings)|bowery's]] second superintendent, [[Jan Everts Bout]]. For many years, the village, often referred to by [[Washington Irving]], existed where the [[Liberty Science Center]] now stands. For hundreds of years it was a [[ferry]] port for local communities of [[Bergen, New Netherland|Bergen]], [[Bergen Township, New Jersey (pre-1862)|Bergen Township]], and [[Hudson County]], as well suburban and long-distance travelers to [[Manhattan]].\n\nIn the latter half of 19th century, a small island named [[Black Tom explosion#Black Tom Island|Black Tom]] was joined via landfill with the mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.state.nj.us/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty_state_park/liberty_blacktomexplosion.html|title=Liberty State Park: Black Tom Explosion|publisher=State of New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection|date=January 26, 2005|access-date=April 8, 2014}}</ref> It became a major shipping, manufacturing, and transportation hub within [[Port of New York and New Jersey]], leading to the construction of [[Communipaw Terminal]]. It was from this ferry/train station that many immigrants arriving at [[Ellis Island]] spread out across the USA. In 1916, on what is now the southeastern corner of the park, the Black Tom explosion killed as many as seven people, caused $20 million in property damage, and was felt throughout the [[Tri-State Region]].\n[[File:LibertyStatePark(pre1976).tif|thumb|left|Before opening, LSP was the site of abandoned rail facilities built on landfills]]\nConstruction of the [[North River Tunnels]], [[containerization]], and the [[Interstate Highway System]], made the area less viable. The decline of industry, deterioration of rail and maritime infrastructure, and toxic waste, eventually made the area obsolete. Abandoned buildings and [[brownfields]] dominated the landscape after the mid-twentieth century, though there was still some manufacturing and recreational use.\n\nAudrey Zapp, Theodore Conrad, Morris Pesin<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmdb.org/Marker.asp?Marker=13294|title=Morris Pesin\u2019s Legendary Canoe Trip Which Launched Liberty State Park Historical Marker|author=|date=|website=HMDb.org|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/22/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/22colnj.html?scp=39&sq=liberty+island&st=nyt | work=The New York Times | first=Kevin | last=Coyne | title=A Quest That Brought Lady Liberty Closer | date=June 22, 2008}}</ref> and [[J. Owen Grundy]] were influential environmentalists and historians who spearheaded the movement that led to the creation of Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folsp.org/grundy_editorial.htm|title=Jersey Journal FOLSP: Jersey Journal|website=FOLSP.org|access-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720184650/http://www.folsp.org/grundy_editorial.htm|archivedate=July 20, 2011}}</ref> They are remembered by the naming of places and streets along the waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1976/06/21/bicentennial-beat|title=Bicentennial Beat|first=Mark|last=Singer|date=June 14, 1976|publisher=|access-date=December 8, 2017|via=www.NewYorker.com}}</ref>\n\nIt is estimated the park suffered $20 million in damages during [[Superstorm Sandy]] in October 2012. In June 2016, the Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal reopened after a $20 million renovation to repair the extensive damage caused by Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2016/06/revamped_liberty_state_park_train_terminal_opens_p.html|title=Historic Liberty State Park train terminal reopens (Photos)|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref> As of December 2019, the Nature Interpretive Center remains closed due to storm damage. No timeline has been given for its completion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ragoza|first=Rafal|title=Latest estimates on Liberty State Park recovery from Hurricane Sandy|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=May 25, 2013|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2013/05/latest_estimates_on_liberty_st.html|accessdate=2013-05-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2015/10/2_senate_democrats_to_hold_hearing_on_future_devel.html|title=Senators want 'secret' DEP report, plan hearing on Liberty State Park's future|author=|date=October 2015|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2018, it was announced by [[New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection]] (NJDEP) that the interior {{convert|240|acre|ha|1}} of the park that have been closed off to the public for decades due to environmental contamination would be remediated into an urban marshland and forest. The restoration is to be done in phases with the initial phase focusing on a {{convert|23|acre|ha|1}} parcel of the interior. The marshland will be fed by a new channel connecting the Hudson River to the park's interior. There is currently no timeline yet for the remediation but the funding is to come from natural resource damage settlements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2018/01/nj_announces_massive_plan_to_restore_240_acres_of.html#incart_river_home|title=N.J. to turn 240 acres of Liberty State Park into wildlife oasis|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=January 11, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Points of interest==\n\n===Freedom Way and Liberty Walkway===\nA road called '''Freedom Way''' goes through the center and serves as a barrier between the area closed to the public, to its west, and the area that is open to the public, to its east. It has many [[bike path]]s, walkways, and fields.\n\n'''Liberty Walkway''', a crescent-shaped promenade, stretches from the [[Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal|CRRNJ Terminal]] along the waterfront south to the Statue of Liberty overlook, bridging two coves along the way. It is part of the longer [[Hudson River Waterfront Walkway]]. Halfway along Liberty Walkway is a bridge to [[Ellis Island]], but only authorized vehicles are allowed.\nThe southeastern corner of the park contains the Statue of Liberty overlook, picnic facilities, a playground, the ''U.S. Flag Plaza'' and ''Liberation Monument'', the Public Administration Building, and a memorial to the [[Black Tom explosion]]s. Picnicking and barbecuing facilities are also located at the southern end of the park. Originally called \"Liberty Walk\",<ref>''Landscape Architecture'' 1991 - Volume 81 Page 69  \"The first phase of the park is the {{convert|1.5|mile|km}} waterfront promenade, Liberty Walk. Construction on the promenade has already begun and will be completed in early 1991; \"</ref><ref>'' Backroads of New Jersey'' 2007 Page 48 \"Take Freedom Way south or walk the {{convert|2|mile|km}} Liberty Walk Promenade through a thirty-six-acre natural area river marsh.\"</ref><ref>Setha Low, Dana Taplin, Suzanne Scheld ''Rethinking Urban Parks: Public Space and Cultural Diversity'' 2009 p. 83 \"...Liberty State Park, includes grass-covered fields, a public boat launch, walkways along the waterfront, spacious parking lots, and ... The other connecting corridor is the {{convert|1.3|mile|km}}-long Liberty Walk, a newly built promenade along the water's edge ...\"</ref> this part of the project won a landscape award in 1995.<ref>Landscape Architecture Magazine 1995 \"Wallace Roberts & Todd (WRT) of Philadelphia and New Jersey's Department of Environmental Protection (NJDEP) were the co-winners of a Top Honor Award for the overall plan and an Honor Award for Liberty State Park and Liberty Walk \"</ref> The name \"Liberty Walk\" was already associated with Philadelphia such as through a booklet ''The Liberty Walk Through Historic Old Philadelphia'' published by the American Wax Museum, Philadelphia (before 1969) which listed a walk round 23 sites of historic interest.\n\n===Liberty Science Center===\nThe [[Liberty Science Center]], at the northwestern entrance to the park, is an interactive science museum and learning center. The center opened in 1993 as New Jersey's first major state [[science museum]]. It has science exhibits, the world's 5th largest [[IMAX Dome]] theater, the largest [[planetarium]] in the Western Hemisphere, numerous educational resources, and the original [[Hoberman sphere]], a silver, computer-driven engineering artwork designed by [[Chuck Hoberman]].<ref>[http://www.nj.gov/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty2.html NJ Department of Parks and Forests] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517032810/http://www.nj.gov/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty2.html |date=2011-05-17 }} Liberty Science Center</ref>\n\n===Monuments and memorials===\n[[File:Empty Sky P6150244.JPG|thumb|''Empty Sky'' Memorial with a remnant from the World Trade Center in the foreground]]\n''[[Liberation (Holocaust memorial)|Liberation]]'' is a 1985 bronze sculpture designed by [[Nathan Rapoport]] as a memorial to the [[Holocaust]], showing a U.S. soldier carrying out a survivor from a [[Nazism|Nazi]] death camp.<ref>[http://www.ettc.net/njarts/details.cfm?ID=424 \"Art and Architecture of New Jersey,\" ETTC.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719035536/http://www.ettc.net/njarts/details.cfm?ID=424 |date=2011-07-19 }}, retrieved May 10, 2011.</ref>\n\n''The Sail of Columbus'' is a two-story sail-shaped bronze monument designed by Gino Gianetti that commemorates the 500th anniversary of the westward journey of [[Christopher Columbus]] to America in 1492. The \"Sail\" sits atop a stone base in the shape of a ship and features scenes of Columbus and his travels.  It was dedicated from the [[Government of Italy]] and the [[Genoa|City of Genoa]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://njcu.libguides.com/jerseycitypastandpresent/libertystatepark|title=Liberty State Park|publisher=New Jersey City University|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[Empty Sky (9-11 memorial)|Empty Sky]]'' is the official state memorial to the [[September 11 attacks]] of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]]. Situated on a berm the parallel walls engraved with the names of victims are oriented to face the former [[World Trade Center site]]. Designed by architect [[Frederic Schwartz]], it was dedicated on September 10, 2011, commemorating the tenth anniversary of the attacks.<ref name=\"nj\">[http://www.state.nj.us/nj911memorial NJ 911 Memorial page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321221751/http://www.state.nj.us/nj911memorial |date=March 21, 2011 }}, retrieved February 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Friends of Liberty State Park filed a lawsuit to block the creation of the 9/11 memorial stating that New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection (DEP) did not provide enough public comment and did not authorize a proper permit linked to the project.  The Friends of Liberty State Park is led by Sam Pesin, the son of Morris Pesin, who first lobbied for the creation of Liberty State Park. Sam Pesin stated that \"The consensus [of park users] is that the memorial as proposed is a massive monstrosity that obstructs powerful views that need protection for future generations,\" he declared. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/lawsuit-against-911-memorial-prompted-threat-river-view|title=Lawsuit Against 9/11 Memorial Prompted by Threat to River View|date=2008-07-07|website=CNSNews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Proposed commercial activities==\nThe [[Governorship of Chris Christie|administration of Governor Chris Christie]] proposed various commercial activities for the park.<ref>http://media.nj.com/hudsoncountynow_impact/other/DEP%20LSP%20report.pdf</ref> In 2017, it suggested leasing large parts of the waterfront for private marinas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2017/12/new_details_about_liberty_state_park_marina_emerge.html|title=Details emerge about new Liberty State Park marina|author=|date=December 2017|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe [[Hudson-Bergen Light Rail]] runs just west of the park with a [[Liberty State Park (HBLR station)|station]] at its entrance. Hornblower Cruises operates ferries to [[Ellis Island]] and [[Liberty Island]], and a [[Liberty Water Taxi|water taxi]] to [[Paulus Hook, Jersey City|Paulus Hook]] and the [[Battery Park City Ferry Terminal]].\n\nIn July 2012, [[North Jersey Transportation Planning Authority]] allotted $175,000 to study transportation alternatives to and within the park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2012/07/jersey_city_receives_grant_to.html|title=Jersey City receives $175,000 state grant to study public-transportation options in Liberty State Park|author=|date=July 2012|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Jersey City received a $500,000 grant to study extending Jersey Avenue from [[Downtown Jersey City|Downtown]] directly into the park, which would simplify access and create a new gateway to the park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/jjournal-news/index.ssf/2013/03/jersey_city_gets_500000_federa.html|title=Jersey City gets $500K federal grant to study extension of road into Liberty State Park|author=|date=March 2013|website=NJ.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> In May 2013, a new pedestrian-bike bridge was placed over Mill Creek at the small basin to replace an older one that had been destroyed by [[Superstorm Sandy]] in October 2012. It is situated so as not interfere with any new road construction.<ref>{{cite news   | last = McDonald   | first = Terrence T.   | title = Seven months after Sandy, a new $800K bridge in Jersey City   | newspaper = The Jersey Journal   | date = May 23, 2013   | url = http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2013/05/seven_months_after_sandy_a_new.html | accessdate = 2013-05-23   | quote = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mill Creek Footbridge|url=http://www.bridgesnyc.com/2013/05/mill-creek-footbridge/|website=bridgesnyc.com|accessdate=2015-01-22}}</ref> In 2014 NJDOT announced that it would build a $10 million bridge over the Morris Canal.\n<ref>{{cite news|last1=McDonald|first1=Terrence T.|title=$10M bridge connecting Downtown Jersey City to Liberty State Park closer to reality|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2014/08/bridge_connecting_downtown_jersey_city_into_liberty_state_park_closer_to_reality.html|accessdate=2015-01-22|publisher=Jersey Journal|date=August 22, 2014}}</ref> Construction of the road began in August 2019; the two-lane road bike paths.<ref>https://www.nj.com/hudson/2019/08/after-decades-of-talk-road-project-connecting-downtown-to-liberty-state-park-bergen-laf-is-underway.html</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[Image:YuvrajrDowntownJerseyCityLSP5.JPG|thumb|right|225px|Liberty Harbor]]\nThe park is featured in the video game ''[[Need for Speed: The Run]]'' towards the end of the game.\n\nIn 2002, [[Budweiser beer|Budweiser]] filmed two commercials to dedicate the [[September 11 attacks]] in the park (one in 2002, and another one in 2011). Both were only aired once<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aol.com/article/finance/2017/09/11/the-story-behind-the-911-budweiser-commercial-that-only-aired-once/23204869/|title=The true story behind the 9/11 Budweiser commercial that only aired once|last=Staff|first=A. O. L.|website=AOL.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref>\n\n===Festivals and performances===\nOn [[Labor Day]] in 1980, Republican Nominee for President [[Ronald Reagan]] kicked off his national campaign on Liberty Island, with the Statue of Liberty behind him and said: 'I want more than anything I've ever wanted, to have an administration that will, through its actions, at home and in the international arena, let millions of people know that Miss Liberty still \"Lifts her lamp beside the golden door.\"' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/reference/9.1.80.html|title=9/1/1980 Speech|author=|date=|website=www.reagan.UTexas.edu|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 1985, [[Hall and Oates|Daryl Hall and John Oates]] played an outdoor benefit concert for the restoration of the Statue of Liberty in front of an estimated 70,000 people at Liberty State Park. The concert was later re-played on HBO.\n\n[[Liberty Weekend#July_4,_1986:_Operation_Sail,_Americana_music_concert,_and_fireworks|| Liberty Weekend]] was a concert event aired on [[ABC Network (United States)|ABC]] on Independence Day, 1984. The concert lineup included [[John Denver]], [[Whitney Houston]], and [[Johnny Cash]].\n\nIn 2000, [[Andrea Bocelli]] gave a concert at the park, broadcast on PBS, as ''American Dream&nbsp;\u2014 the Statue of Liberty concert''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bocellicentralpark.com/the-worlds-most-beloved-tenor-andrea-bocelli-gifts-new-york-city-with-a-once-in-a-lifetime-musical-event|title=Universal Music Group, the world's leading music company - Home Page - UMG|author=|date=|website=UMG|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, [[Cirque du Soleil]] premiered its new work.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/13/movies/circus-review-dancing-lion-eerie-dragon-in-a-time-warp.html?scp=1&sq=Cirque%20du%20Soleil%20liberty%20State&st=cse | work=The New York Times | first=Lawrence | last=Van Gelder | title=CIRCUS REVIEW; Dancing Lion, Eerie Dragon in a Time Warp | date=April 13, 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the park began to host the Liberty [[Jazz Festival]]. This two-day event is normally held the first weekend after [[Labor Day]] each year and has included performers such as [[George Benson]], [[Waymon Tisdale]] and other jazz artists.\n\nFrom August 8\u201310, 2008, the park was the site of the [[All Points West Music & Arts Festival]]; the park hosted the festival again from July 31 to August 2, 2009, with such acts as [[Jay-Z]], [[Coldplay]], [[Tool (band)|Tool]], and [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]].\n\n===Film and TV===\n* In 1968, the film ''[[Funny Girl (film)|Funny Girl]]'' shot the \"[[Don't Rain on My Parade]]\" sequence in the Central Railroad of NJ Terminal.<ref name=\"LSP\">{{cite web|url=https://jerseydigs.com/liberty-state-park-jersey-city-history|title=Liberty State Park: New Jersey\u2019s Gift to America|website=jerseydigs.com|date=July 12, 2017|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* In 1971, the famous ''[[The Godfather]]'' (1972) scene containing [[Peter Clemenza]] and Rocco Lampone's famous exchange, \"Leave the gun. Take the cannoli\", was filmed at the site before the construction of Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoutingny.com/the-godfather-the-new-york-city-filming-locations-then-and-now/2/|title=The New York Filming Locations of The Godfather, Then and Now - Scouting NY - Page 2|author=|date=|website=www.ScoutingNY.com|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1997, the film ''[[Men in Black (1997 film)|Men in Black]]'' depicts a scene where [[Agent J]] delivers a newborn alien squid on Morris Pesin Drive.<ref name=\"LSP\"/>\n* In 2014, the movie, ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'', was shot at Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onthesetofnewyork.com/annie2014.html|title=Annie Film Locations|website=onthesetofnewyork.com|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*In the 2018 Netflix series ''[[Seven Seconds (TV series)|Seven Seconds]]'', the bicycle accident at the center of the plot of season 1 occurs at Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/hudson/2018/02/netflix_drama_explores_racial_tensions_police_cove.html|title=Netflix drama explores racial unrest, police cover-up in Jersey City|website=nj.com|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nSince 2007, the [[Veuve Clicquot]] Polo Classic is held every Spring at Liberty State Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2018/06/veuve_clicquot_polo_classic_returns_to_liberty_sta.html|title=Veuve Clicquot Polo Classic returns to Liberty State Park with star-studded guest list (PHOTOS)|publisher=The Jersey Journal|date=June 2, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, plans were put forth outlining the use of the park as the new home of the [[United States Grand Prix|United States]] [[Formula One]] [[Grand Prix motor racing|Grand Prix]] for the [[2012 Formula One season|2012 season]].<ref>{{cite news|title=New York F1 track plans revealed&nbsp;\u2013 Jersey City bids for 2012 night race|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2010/05/04/new-york-f1-track-plans-revealed-jersey-city-bids-for-new-night-race-in-2012/|first=Keith|last=Collantine|work=F1 Fanatic|publisher=Keith Collantine|date=2010-05-04|accessdate=2010-05-04|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5w707hQJk?url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2010/05/04/new-york-f1-track-plans-revealed-jersey-city-bids-for-new-night-race-in-2012/|archive-date=2011-01-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> These plans met outrage from the community, particularly the Friends of Liberty State Park, and were ultimately rejected by the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folsp.org/preservation/grand_prix.htm|title=folsp.org|website=FOLSP.org|access-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605174724/http://www.folsp.org/preservation/grand_prix.htm|archivedate=June 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19 and 20, 2010, the park hosted the fifth round of the [[2010 Red Bull Air Race World Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2010/06/countdown_to_jersey_city_red_b.html|title=About the Red Bull Air Race in Jersey City|newspaper=The Jersey Journal|date=June 4, 2010|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"125\">\nFile:Lsp flag display.jpg|Twelve out of the 13 [[Flag of the United States|American Flags]] displayed at Liberty State Park (one flag not shown), with the Statue of Liberty in the background\nFile:CRRNJ Terminal, Liberty State Park, Jersey City NJ.jpg|[[Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal|Communipaw Terminal]], historic building.  Dock in foreground serves ferries to Ellis Island and Statue of Liberty\nFile:Parkflags.jpg|Flags at [[half-staff]] in Liberty State Park\nFile:Central Railroad of New Jersey Ferry Terminal.jpg|Communipaw Terminal\nFile:Twintowers1999.JPG|In 1999\nFile:Liberty State Park from One World Observatory June 2015.JPG|As seen from [[One World Trade Center]] in June 2015\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New Jersey}}\n* [[List of New Jersey state parks]]\n* [[Hudson River Waterfront Walkway]]\n* [[Hudson County, New Jersey#Parks|Hudson Parks]]\n* [[Port of New York and New Jersey]]\n* [[Marine life of New York-New Jersey Harbor Estuary]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|{{#property:Commons category}}}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.state.nj.us/dep/parksandforests/parks/liberty.html}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100201224707/http://www.njcu.edu/programs/jchistory/pages/c_pages/central_Railroad_of_New_Jersey.html Central Railroad of New Jersey Terminal]\n* [http://www.folsp.org Friends of Liberty State Park], an advocacy group for the park's preservation\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9D05EFD6163DE633A2575BC0A9669D946296D6CF ''The New York Times''], 1913 proposal to develop Jersey City port facilities\n* {{cite report   | title = Liberty State Park Ecosystem Restoration Study   | work = Hudson-Raritan Estuary    | publisher = USACE   | date = October 2005   | url = http://www.nan.usace.army.mil/Portals/37/docs/civilworks/projects/nj/ecor/HRELiberty/realestate.pdf   | format = PDF   | accessdate =}}\n\n{{New Jersey Parks}}\n{{Hudson County Parks, New Jersey}}\n{{Nature centers in New Jersey}}\n{{Jersey City Neighborhoods}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:State parks of New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Parks in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Urban public parks]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Parks on the Hudson River]]\n[[Category:Redeveloped ports and waterfronts in the United States]]\n[[Category:Nature centers in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Geography of Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Vaishali More", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u092e\u0930\u093e\u0920\u0940\u0924 \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e\u0902\u0924\u0930)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liberty_State_Park"}
{"title_page": "Samuel J. Tilden", "text_new": "{{short description|19th-century American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Samuel Tilden\n|image        = SamuelJonesTilden.jpg\n|order        = 25th [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]\n|lieutenant   = [[William Dorsheimer]]\n|term_start   = January 1, 1875\n|term_end     = December 31, 1876\n|predecessor  = [[John Adams Dix]]\n|successor    = [[Lucius Robinson]]\n|office1      = Member of the [[New York State Assembly]]<br>from [[Manhattan|New York County]]'s 18th district\n|term_start1  = January 1, 1872\n|term_end1    = December 31, 1872\n|predecessor1 = Leander Buck\n|successor1   = [[Biglin Brothers|Barney Biglin]]\n|office2      = Chair of the [[New York State Democratic Committee|New York Democratic Party]]\n|term_start2  = August 1866\n|term_end2    = September 1874\n|predecessor2 = [[Dean Richmond]]\n|successor2   = [[Allen C. Beach]]\n|office3      = Member of the New York State Assembly from [[Manhattan|New York County]]\n|alongside3   = 13 others<br/>(Multi-member district)\n|term_start3  = 1846\n|term_end3    = 1847\n|predecessor3 = Various (Multi-member district)\n|successor3   = Various (Multi-member district)\n|office4      = [[New York City Law Department|Corporation Counsel]] of [[New York City]]\n|term_start4  = 1843\n|term_end4    = 1844\n|predecessor4 = Alexander W. Bradford\n|successor4   = Stephen Sammons\n|birth_name   = Samuel Jones Tilden\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1814|2|9}}\n|birth_place  = [[New Lebanon, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1886|8|4|1814|2|9}}\n|death_place  = [[Yonkers, New York]], U.S.\n|restingplace = [[Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument]], Cemetery of the Evergreens, New Lebanon, New York\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[Yale University]]<br>[[New York University]]\n|signature    = Samuel Tilden Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Samuel Jones Tilden ''' (February 9, 1814 \u2013 August 4, 1886) was the 25th [[Governor of New York]] and the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] candidate for president in the [[1876 United States presidential election|disputed election of 1876]]. As of 2020, Tilden is the only individual to [[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|win an outright majority of the popular vote]] in a [[United States presidential election]] but lose the election.{{efn|As of 2020, four candidates have lost a presidential election despite garnering a [[plurality (voting)|plurality]] of the popular vote; [[Andrew Jackson]] in [[1824 United States presidential election|1824]]; [[Grover Cleveland]] in [[1888 United States presidential election|1888]]; [[Al Gore]] in [[2000 United States presidential election|2000]]; and [[Hillary Clinton]] in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kernell |first1=Samuel |last2=Jacobson |first2=Gary C. |last3=Kousser |first3=Thad |last4=Vavreck |first4=Lynn |date=2020 |title=The Logic of American Politics |edition=Ninth |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vKR0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA507 |location=Thousand Oaks, CA |publisher=CQ Press |page=507 |isbn=978-1-5443-2301-5 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>}} \n\nTilden was born into a wealthy family in [[New Lebanon, New York]]. Attracted to politics at a young age, he became a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Martin Van Buren]], the eighth [[President of the United States]]. After studying at [[Yale University]] and [[New York University School of Law]], Tilden began a legal career in [[New York City]], becoming a noted corporate lawyer. He served in the [[New York State Assembly]] and helped launch Van Buren's [[third party (United States)|third party]], anti-[[slavery in the United States|slavery]] candidacy in the [[1848 United States presidential election|1848 presidential election]]. Though he opposed the election of [[Abraham Lincoln]] in 1860, Tilden supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] during the [[American Civil War]]. After the Civil War, Tilden was selected as the chairman of the [[New York State Democratic Committee]], and he managed Democratic nominee [[Horatio Seymour]]'s campaign in the [[1868 United States presidential election|1868 presidential election]]. \n\nTilden initially cooperated with the state party's [[Tammany Hall]] faction, but he broke with them in 1871 due to boss [[William M. Tweed]]'s rampant corruption. Tilden won election as [[Governor of New York]] in 1874, and in that office he helped break up the \"[[Canal Ring (New York)|Canal Ring]].\" Tilden's battle against public corruption, along with his personal fortune and electoral success in the country's most populous state, made him the leading candidate for the Democratic nomination for president in 1876. Tilden was selected as the nominee on the second ballot of the [[1876 Democratic National Convention]]. In the general election, Tilden faced [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Rutherford B. Hayes]], another governor with reform credentials. Tilden focused his campaign on civil service reform, support for the [[gold standard]], and opposition to high taxes, but many of his supporters were more concerned with ending [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] in the South.\n\nMost observers initially believed that Tilden had won the election, but disputes in four states left both Tilden and Hayes without a majority of the [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral vote]]. As Tilden had won 184 electoral votes, one vote shy of a majority, a Hayes victory required that he sweep all of the disputed electoral votes. Against Tilden's wishes, Congress appointed the bipartisan [[Electoral Commission (United States)|Electoral Commission]] to settle the controversy. Republicans had a one-seat advantage on the Electoral Commission, and in a series of party-line rulings, ruled that Hayes had won all of the disputed electoral votes. In the [[Compromise of 1877]], Democratic leaders agreed to accept Hayes as the victor in return for the end of Reconstruction. Tilden was a major contender for the Democratic presidential nomination in the [[1880 United States presidential election|1880]] and [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential elections]], but declined to run.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[Image:SamuelJTilden.jpeg|thumb|Samuel Tilden as a young man]]\n\nTilden was born in [[New Lebanon, New York]], the youngest son of Elam Tilden and Polly Jones Tilden.<ref>Bigelow (2009), pp. 12\u201315</ref> He was descended from [[Tylden (family)|Nathaniel Tilden]], an early [[English people|English]] settler who came to [[North America]] in 1634. His father and other family members were the makers of [[Tilden's Extract]], a popular [[patent medicine]] of the 1800s and early 1900s derived from [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]].<ref>William Lee Richter, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cyGb-eMnmXkC&pg=PA610 ''Historical Dictionary of the Civil War and Reconstruction''], 2004, page 610</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=psbmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA117 Obituary, Samuel J. Tilden (nephew of New York Governor)], ''The Pharmaceutical Era'', March 1914, p. 117</ref> Tilden's father maintained relationships with many influential politicians, including President [[Martin Van Buren]], who became Tilden's political idol.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 85</ref> Tilden was frequently in poor health during his youth, and he spent much of his time studying politics and reading works such as ''[[The Wealth of Nations]]''.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 85</ref> Tilden's health troubles prevented him from regularly attending school, and he dropped out of [[Yale University]] after a single term.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 84\u201386</ref>\n\nLikely motivated by a family friendship with [[Benjamin Franklin Butler (lawyer)|Benjamin Franklin Butler]], then serving as a professor at [[New York University School of Law]], Tilden enrolled there to resume his studies, and he continued to attend intermittently from 1838 to 1841.<ref>{{cite book|title=The life and public services of Hon. Samuel J. Tilden: Democratic nominee ...|author=Theodore Pease Cook|page=9}}</ref> While studying at NYU, Tilden also [[reading law|read law]] in the office of attorney [[John W. Edmonds]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Scharf |first=John Thomas |date=1886 |title=History of Westchester County, New York |volume=Volume 1, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EkgVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA504 |location=Philadelphia, PA |publisher=L. E. Preston & Co. |page=554 |ref={{sfnRef|''History of Westchester County, New York''}}}}</ref> He was admitted to the bar in 1841 and became a skilled [[corporate lawyer]].{{sfn|''History of Westchester County, New York''|page=554}} Tilden affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], and he frequently campaigned on behalf of Van Buren and other Democratic candidates.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 86\u201389</ref>\n\n== Early political career ==\n[[File:MVanBuren.png|thumb|upright=0.9|Tilden was a protege of [[Martin Van Buren]], the 8th [[President of the United States]].]]\n\nIn 1843, as a reward for campaign work on behalf of Governor [[William C. Bouck]], Tilden was appointed as New York City's corporation counsel.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 89</ref> Tilden handled hundreds of cases on behalf of the city, but was forced out of office in 1844 after New York City elected a [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] mayor.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 90</ref> He served as a delegate to the [[1844 Democratic National Convention]], which rejected Van Buren and nominated [[James K. Polk]] for president.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 90</ref> At the urging of Governor [[Silas Wright]], Tilden won election to the [[New York State Assembly]].<ref>Morris (2003), p. 91</ref> He became a key ally to Wright and helped end the [[Anti-Rent War]] by passing a compromise land bill that defused tensions between tenant farmers and their landlords.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 91\u201392</ref> After serving as a delegate to the 1846 [[New York State Constitutional Convention]], Tilden left public office to focus on his legal practice, where he gained a national reputation as a \"financial physician\" for struggling railroads.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 89\u201393</ref> Tilden's successful legal practice, combined with shrewd investments, made him rich.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kessner |first=Thomas |date=2003 |title=Capital City: New York City and the Men Behind America's Rise to Economic |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PefKIplMWrUC&pg=PA185 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Simon & Schuster |page=185 |isbn=978-0-7432-5753-4 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> His success at money management and investing caused many of his friends, relatives, and political allies, including Van Buren, to allow Tilden to manage their finances.<ref>Severn (1968), p. 64</ref>\n\nTilden helped to found the \"[[Barnburner]]s\", an anti-[[slavery in the United States|slavery]] faction of the New York Democratic Party that arose in the midst of the debate over the [[Wilmot Proviso]]. Like other Barnburners, Tilden sought to prevent the spread of slavery into the [[Mexican cession|land acquired from Mexico]] in the [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo]]. He helped organize the 1848 [[Free Soil Party|Free Soil]] Convention, which nominated Van Buren for president. Van Buren's candidacy in the [[1848 United States presidential election|1848 presidential election]] may have played a role in the victory of Whig nominee [[Zachary Taylor]] over Democratic nominee [[Lewis Cass]]. Unlike many other anti-slavery Democrats, Tilden did not join the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] in the 1850s, but he did not have close relations with Democratic presidents [[Franklin Pierce]] and [[James Buchanan]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 94\u201395</ref> In [[New York state election, 1855|1855]], Tilden was the unsuccessful [[New York State Attorney General|state attorney general]] candidate of the \"[[Hunkers and Barnburners|Soft]]\" faction of Barnburners, which favored compromise and reconciliation with the Democratic Party.<ref>Robinson (2001), p. 85</ref> In [[New York state election, 1859|1859]], after he lost an election to serve as New York City's corporation counsel, Tilden announced that he was \"out of politics.\"<ref>Morris (2003), p. 95</ref>\n\nIn the [[1860 United States presidential election|1860 presidential election]], Tilden strongly opposed the candidacy of Republican presidential nominee [[Abraham Lincoln]]. He warned that the election of Lincoln could lead to the secession of the South and a subsequent civil war.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 95\u201396</ref> Tilden initially opposed using force to prevent secession, but he supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] after the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]]. Tilden served as the manager of [[Horatio Seymour]]'s successful 1862 campaign for governor, and played a key role in securing the nomination of [[George B. McClellan]] at the [[1864 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 96\u201397</ref>\n\nIn 1867, Tilden received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from [[New York University]].<ref>{{cite book |last=General Alumni Society, New York University |date=1906 |title=General Alumni Catalogue |url=https://archive.org/details/generalalumnica01univgoog |location=New York, NY |publisher=New York University |page=170}}</ref> He was also chosen as a delegate to that year's [[New York Constitution#Constitutional Convention of 1867\u20131868|state constitutional convention]].<ref>{{cite news |date=June 4, 1867 |title=The Constitutional Convention to Assemble To-Day |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/329585675/ |work=[[New York Herald]] |location=New York, NY |url-access=subscription |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |page=7}}</ref>\n\n== State party leader ==\n[[File:SamuelTilden.png|thumb|right|upright|A portrait of Samuel Jones Tilden]]\n\nFollowing the end of the Civil War, Tilden won election as the chairman of the [[New York State Democratic Committee]]. He served as Seymour's campaign chairman in the [[1868 United States presidential election|1868 presidential election]], but Seymour lost the election to Republican nominee [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 97\u201398</ref> After the election, Tilden broke with [[William M. Tweed]], the leader of the [[Tammany Hall]] [[political machine]]. Through bribery, patronage, and control of [[Irish-American]] voters, Tweed and his allies had become the dominant power in both New York City and the state of New York.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 99\u2013102</ref> In 1871, former Tammany associate [[James O'Brien (U.S. Congressman)|James O'Brien]] leaked Tweed's account books to the ''[[New York Times]]''. The ''Times'' subsequently began a public crusade against Tammany Hall, and Tilden launched an investigation into Tweed's bank records. Tilden ran for the New York State Assembly as part of a slate of anti-Tammany Democrats; at the state party convention, he declared that it was \"time to proclaim that whoever plunders the people, though he steal the livery of heaven to serve the devil in, is no Democrat.\" The anti-Tammany Democrats, including Tilden, won a major victory in the [[New York state election, 1871|1871 state elections]], and Tweed was indicted on 120 counts of fraud and other violations. After the election, Tweed fled the state, but he was eventually extradited back to New York, where he died in prison in 1878.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nTilden's role in taking down Tweed bolstered his popularity, and he was elected Governor of New York in [[New York state election, 1874|1874]]. As governor, he continued to focus on rooting out corruption. He helped to break up the \"[[Canal Ring (New York)|Canal Ring]],\" a bipartisan group of state and local officials who had enriched themselves by overcharging for the maintenance of the [[New York State Canal System]]. Tilden gained a national reputation as a reform governor, a valuable asset given the number of [[Grant administration scandals|scandals]] that had come into public view during the [[presidency of Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 104\u2013105</ref>\n\nIn 1875, Tilden received an honorary LL.D. from [[Yale University]].<ref name=Yale_Catalogue>{{cite book |last=Yale University |date=1877 |title=Catalogue of the Officers and Graduates of Yale University |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=UahGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA51 |location=New Haven, CT |publisher=Morehouse and Taylor |page=51}}</ref> At the same time, Yale also enrolled him as a graduate of the Class of 1837 and he received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree.<ref name=\"Yale_Catalogue\"/>\n\n==Presidential election of 1876==\n{{See also|Samuel Tilden presidential campaign, 1876}}\n\n===Democratic nomination===\n[[Image:Tilden and Hendricks campaign poster.jpg|thumb|Campaign poster for the election of 1876]]\n\nBy the time of the June [[1876 Democratic National Convention]], Tilden had emerged as the front-runner for the Democratic nomination in the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 presidential election]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 106</ref> Tilden's appeal to the national party was based on his reputation for reform and his electoral success in the country's most populous state. He was also a skilled organizer whose canvassing system and field knowledge was so thorough that, months before the 1874 election, he'd predicted his own winning margin accurately to within 300 votes.<ref>Holt (2008), p. 100</ref> Tilden further bolstered his presidential candidacy through a nationwide newspaper advertising campaign. As many Democrats expected that their party would win the 1876 presidential elections, Tilden faced competition from some of the party's most prominent leaders, including [[Thomas F. Bayard]], [[Allen G. Thurman]], [[Thomas A. Hendricks]], and General [[Winfield Scott Hancock]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 106\u2013107</ref>\n\nDuring the difficult economic times of the [[Panic of 1873]], the major ideological divide in the Democratic Party concerned the issue of [[History of monetary policy in the United States|currency]]. Many \"soft money\" Democrats wanted Congress to repeal the [[Specie Payment Resumption Act]] and authorize the printing of more [[greenback (money)|greenback]]s, [[banknotes]] that had first been printed during the Civil War. The printing of more greenbacks would result in [[inflation]] and potentially benefit farmers by raising prices and helping them pay down their debts. Like most Republicans and \"hard money\" members of the conservative business establishment, Tilden believed that the termination of greenback circulation (which would return the country to the [[gold standard]]) was the best way to solve the ongoing economic crisis. Tilden's lieutenants at the Democratic National Convention emphasized Tilden's reform credentials above all else, but they also ensured that the party platform endorsed Tilden's hard money views.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 108\u2013109, 112\u2013114</ref> \n\nTilden won a majority of the votes cast on the first presidential ballot of the convention, but fell short of the two-thirds majority required to win the Democratic presidential nomination. His closest rival was Hendricks, who had the support of New York party boss [[John Kelly (New York politician)|John Kelly]] and the soft money faction of Democrats. Tilden won the necessary two-thirds majority on the second presidential ballot, and the convention then voted to make his nomination unanimous. Delegates unanimously chose Hendricks as Tilden's running mate, providing a balance between the hard money and soft money factions.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 115\u2013117</ref> Though the Republicans had nominated a ticket led by [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] of Ohio, another governor who had established a reputation for honest governance, Tilden was widely regarded as the favorite in the general election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 80\u201383, 122</ref>\n\n===General election===\n[[File:1876 U.S. presidential election, contested states.png|thumb|upright=1.5|In the aftermath of the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 presidential election]], the electoral votes of four states were disputed.]]\n\nPer tradition, both Tilden and Hayes avoided publicly campaigning for president, leaving that task to their supporters; Tilden appointed [[Abram Hewitt]] to lead his campaign.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 123, 131\u2013132</ref> The Republican campaign established a major cash advantage, partly because Tilden refused to contribute much of his personal fortune to the campaign.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 121</ref> The Democrats campaigned on the theme of \"retrenchment and reform\" and attacked the \"corrupt centralism\" of the Grant administration.<ref name=\"morris118120\"/> Tilden blamed high taxes and the Grant administration for the economic downturn, and, like Hayes, promised [[U.S. Civil Service Reform|civil service reform]] and hard money policies.<ref>White (2017), pp. 328\u2013330</ref> Republicans, meanwhile, focused on their party's identification with Lincoln and the Union cause in the Civil War; many Republicans still associated the Democratic Party with slavery and disunion.<ref name=\"morris118120\">Morris (2003), pp. 118\u2013120</ref> Rebutting Republican charges, Tilden categorically denied that he had any intention of compensating the South for any slaves emancipated or losses suffered during the Civil War.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 161\u2013162</ref> For their part, many Democrats cared little for Tilden's emphasis on reform, and were instead focused on ending sixteen years of Republican leadership. Southern Democrats especially hoped to end [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] and gain control of South Carolina, Florida, and Louisiana, the last three \"[[Redeemers|unredeemed]]\" Southern states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 125\u2013126, 146</ref> Southern whites, who overwhelmingly favored Tilden, used violence and intimidation to suppress the turnout of Republican-leaning [[African-American]] voters.<ref>White (2017), pp. 330\u2013331</ref> Tilden worked to distance himself from violent encounters like the [[Hamburg massacre]], in which disgruntled Southern whites clashed with the Republican-led government of South Carolina.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 129\u2013131</ref>\n\nBoth campaigns considered New York, Ohio, and Indiana to be the key [[swing states]], but the campaigns also focused on several smaller states, including the three unredeemed Southern states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 155\u2013156</ref> Ultimately, Hayes swept the West and won much of the North, but Tilden carried the closely contested Northern states of New York, New Jersey, Indiana, and Connecticut, swept the [[border states (American Civil War)|border states]], and carried most of the South. He had won a majority of the popular vote and tallied clear victories in seventeen states, leaving him one [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral vote]] short of a majority. On November 6, the day after election day, most major newspapers reported that Tilden had won the election; however, Hayes still had a narrow path to victory if he could sweep the electoral votes of Florida, South Carolina, and Louisiana.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 164\u2013166</ref> Hayes refused to formally concede, but told members of the press that he was \"of the opinion that the Democrats have carried the country and elected Tilden.\"<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 167\u2013171</ref> Tilden, meanwhile, urged his alarmed followers, many of whom believed that the Republicans were attempting to steal the election, to remain calm and refrain from violence. Both parties feared the possibility that a dispute over the election would lead to armed conflict; Tilden discussed appointing General [[George B. McClellan]] as his military assistant, while President Grant ordered army and naval units to reinforce Washington.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 172\u2013174</ref>\n\n===Post-election controversy===\n[[Image:SJTilden of NY.jpg|thumb|right|Samuel Jones Tilden]]\n\nWith the election in doubt, each party sent some of their most prominent leaders to monitor the election process in the three disputed Southern states. Initial election returns showed that Hayes had carried South Carolina by several hundred votes, but that Tilden had won Florida by 91 votes and Louisiana by over 6000 votes. Republicans controlled the bodies charged with determining the validity of election results in all three states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 174\u2013178</ref> On November 22, the South Carolina canvassing board adjourned after declaring that Hayes had won the state's electoral votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 180\u2013182</ref> On December 4, the Louisiana canvassing board announced that it had thrown out 15,623 votes due to \"systemic intimidation,\" leaving Hayes as the winner of all of the state's electoral votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 191\u2013192</ref> Early on the morning of December 6, the day the Electoral College was scheduled to convene, the Florida canvassing board announced that Hayes had won the state by a margin of 924 votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 193\u2013197</ref> Democrats challenged the results in all three contested Southern states. Meanwhile, another controversy had arisen in Oregon, where a Hayes elector, John Watts, resigned because his simultaneous service as a presidential elector and as a low-ranking official in the [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office]] violated the [[United States Constitution]]. After Watts resigned, the state's Democratic governor appointed an elector to fill the vacancy, while, separately, the state's two remaining Hayes electors chose a third elector to fill the vacancy caused by Watts's resignation.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 183\u2013185, 197\u2013198</ref>\n\nOn December 6, the members of the Electoral College met in Washington, D.C., but the disputes in four states prevented a conclusive vote for president.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 197\u2013198</ref> With the Electoral College unable to select a president, the disputed election became an issue for Congress to settle; Republicans controlled the Senate, while Democrats controlled the House. The vague wording of the Constitution gave rise to further controversy, as Republicans held that [[Thomas W. Ferry]], a Republican senator from Michigan and the [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|president pro tempore]] of the [[United States Senate]], could determine the validity of the disputed electoral votes. Democrats argued that Ferry could only count the votes that were not disputed; in such a scenario, neither candidate would have an electoral vote majority, necessitating a [[contingent election]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. Since Democrats controlled a majority of the state delegations in the House, they would be able to elect Tilden as president in a contingent election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 200\u2013201</ref> In response to the controversy, Tilden compiled his own study of electoral procedures in the previous 22 presidential elections. He delivered the study to every sitting member of Congress, but congressional Republicans were not swayed by Tilden's argument that history supported the Democratic position on the election returns.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 203\u2013204</ref> He continued to call for calm, and rejected Abram Hewitt's suggestion that he ask his supporters to engage in mass public demonstrations.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 206\u2013207, 214</ref>\n\n===Electoral Commission===\n[[File:President Rutherford Hayes 1870 - 1880 Restored.jpg|thumb|upright=1|[[Rutherford B. Hayes]] defeated Tilden in the 1876 election.]]\n\nOn January 26, both houses of Congress agreed to establish the 15-member [[Electoral Commission (United States)|Electoral Commission]] to settle the dispute over the contested electoral votes. The commission consisted of five Democratic members of Congress, five Republican members of Congress, and five justices of the [[Supreme Court of the United States]]. Of the Supreme Court justices, two were to be Democrats, two were to be Republicans, and the fifth justice would be selected by the other four justices. Tilden opposed the creation of the Electoral Commission because he still hoped to force a contingent election in the House of Representatives, but he was unable to prevent Democratic congressmen from voting for the establishment of the commission. Most had expected that the fifth justice on the commission would be Associate Justice [[David Davis (Supreme Court justice)|David Davis]], a [[political independent]], but Davis refused to serve on the commission after he accepted election to the Senate. Another associate justice, Republican [[Joseph P. Bradley]], was instead chosen as the fifth justice on the Electoral Commission.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 216\u2013219</ref> In a series of 8-to-7, party-line decisions, the Electoral Commission voted to award all of the contested electoral votes to Hayes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 222\u2013235</ref>\n\nEven after the Electoral Commission delivered its rulings, the House of Representatives could have blocked the inauguration of Hayes by refusing to certify the election results.<ref>White (2017), p. 332</ref> Though some House Democrats hoped to do just that, they were unable to prevent the House of Representatives from blocking certification, as many House Democrats joined with their Republican colleagues in accepting the results.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 235\u2013236</ref> During the proceedings of the Electoral Commission, high-ranking members of both parties had discussed the possibility of declaring Hayes the winner in exchange for the removal of all federal troops from the South. The [[Compromise of 1877]], as it became known, may have played a role in preventing the House from challenging the Electoral Commission's rulings, although author Roy Morris, Jr. argues that the compromise \"was more a mutual concession of the obvious than a device for controlling larger events.\"<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 232\u2013234</ref> Some other historians, including [[C. Vann Woodward]], have argued that the Compromise of 1877 played the decisive role in determining the outcome of the election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kleinfeld |first1=N. R. |title=COUNTING THE VOTE: THE HISTORY; President Tilden? No, but Almost, in Another Vote That Dragged On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/us/counting-vote-history-president-tilden-no-but-almost-another-vote-that-dragged.html |accessdate=6 November 2018 |newspaper=New York Times |date=12 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Review: NOT A COMPROMISE |journal=The Review of Politics |date=2009 |volume=71 |issue=4 |pages=698\u2013700 |jstor=25655882}}</ref> On March 2, two days before the end of Grant's term, Congress declared Hayes the victor of the 1876 presidential election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 237\u2013238</ref> Hayes took office on March 4, and withdrew the last federal soldiers from the South in April 1877, bringing an end to the Reconstruction Era.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 240, 244\u2013245</ref>\n\nSome Democrats urged Tilden to reject the results and take the presidential [[oath of office]], but Tilden declined to do so. On March 3, the House passed a resolution declaring Tilden the \"duly elected President of the United States,\" but this had no legal effect.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 241\u2013242</ref> Tilden himself stated that, \"I can retire to private life with the consciousness that I shall receive from posterity the credit of having been elected to the highest position in the gift of the people, without any of the cares and responsibilities of the office.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=King |first=Gilbert |date=September 7, 2012 |title=The Ugliest, Most Contentious Presidential Election Ever |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/the-ugliest-most-contentious-presidential-election-ever-28429530/ |magazine=Smithsonian Magazine |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Smithsonian Institution}}</ref> Tilden was the second individual, after [[Andrew Jackson]] in 1824, to lose a presidential election [[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|despite winning at least a plurality of the popular vote]].<ref name=\"Revesz\">{{cite news |last1=Revesz |first1=Rachel |title=Five presidential nominees who won popular vote but lost the election |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/popular-vote-electoral-college-five-presidential-nominees-hillary-clinton-al-gore-a7420971.html |accessdate=6 November 2018 |newspaper=The Independent |date=16 November 2016}}</ref>[[Grover Cleveland]] (1888), [[Al Gore]] (2000), and [[Hillary Clinton]] (2016) subsequently won pluralities while losing the electoral vote.<ref name=\"Revesz\"/> Tilden remains the only individual to lose a presidential election while winning an outright majority of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Law |first=Tara |date=May 15, 2019 |title=These Presidents Won the Electoral College \u2014 But Not the Popular Vote |url=https://time.com/5579161/presidents-elected-electoral-college/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |location=New York, NY |publisher=Time USA, LLC}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n===Potter Committee===\n[[Image:STilden.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Samuel Tilden]]\n\nIn 1878, Democratic Congressman [[Clarkson Nott Potter]] convinced the House of Representatives to create a committee to investigate allegations of fraud and corruption in the 1876 election. Potter was appointed as the head of the commission, which Democrats hoped would implicate Hayes and damage the Republican Party in the next presidential election.<ref>Guenther (1983), 284\u2013285</ref> Rather than produce conclusive evidence of Republican malfeasance, the committee uncovered conflicting evidence that reflected poorly on election and campaign officials of both parties. For ten months beginning in May 1878, the Potter Committee subpoenaed all telegrams sent by political operatives during the election dispute. 29,275 telegrams had been sent, but all save 641 had been routinely destroyed by [[Western Union]]. The remaining telegrams were in cipher, as was common with business and political communication in the telegraph era. ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' editor [[Whitelaw Reid]] obtained and deciphered many of the telegrams and, in October 1878, he published the story of the Democratic efforts to sway election officials through bribery and other means. The revelation of the bribery attempts undercut the Democratic Party's argument that Tilden had been cheated out of the presidency.<ref>Kahn (1996), pp. 221\u2013229</ref> Tilden was not implicated in any wrongdoing, but the investigation into the Cipher Telegrams damaged his national standing.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 250\u2013251</ref>\n\n===Election of 1880===\n\nAfter the controversy over the election of 1876, Tilden became the presumptive Democratic candidate in [[1880 United States presidential election|1880 presidential election]]. He declined to run for another term as governor in 1879, focusing instead on building support for the 1880 presidential nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), p. 52</ref> The revelations of the Potter Committee, along with Tilden's persistent health issues, both damaged Tilden's national standing, but his superior political organization and personal fortune ensured that he remained a serious contender for the Democratic nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 56\u201357</ref> Tilden's standing with the party slipped further following the Republican victory in the [[New York state election, 1879|New York gubernatorial election in 1879]]. In that election, a revitalized Tammany Hall organization split from the regular Democratic party in a patronage dispute with Tilden's faction.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 61\u201363</ref> In the months before the [[1880 Democratic National Convention]], rumors about Tilden's intentions circulated wildly, but Tilden refused to definitively state whether or not he would seek the Democratic nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 74\u201375</ref>\n\nAs the New York delegation left for the national convention in Cincinnati, Tilden gave a letter to one of his chief supporters, [[Daniel Manning]], suggesting that his health might force him to decline the nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 122\u2013123</ref> Tilden hoped to be nominated, but only if he was the unanimous choice of the convention; if not, Manning was entrusted to make the contents of Tilden's letter available to the New York delegation.<ref name=\"Goldman\">{{cite book |last=Goldman |first=Andrew |date=2015 |orig-year=1990 |title=The National Party Chairmen and Committees |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e0agDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT107 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Routledge |page=107 |isbn=978-1-3154-9067-0}}</ref> The New York delegation interpreted the letter as a notice of withdrawal, and the delegates began looking for a new candidate, eventually settling on Speaker of the House [[Samuel J. Randall]].<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 124\u2013126, 139</ref> Ultimately, the party nominated [[Winfield Scott Hancock]], who lost the election to [[James A Garfield]].<ref name=\"Goldman\"/>{{rp|108-109}} Though many Democrats favored Tilden for the party's nomination in the [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential election]], Tilden once again declined to run due to poor health.<ref name=\"Goldman\"/>{{rp|110}} He endorsed New York Governor [[Grover Cleveland]], who won the Democratic nomination and went on to defeat [[James G. Blaine]] in the general election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 255\u2013256</ref>\n\n===Retirement and death===\n[[File:Tilden 112 cu jeh.jpg|thumb|Statue in New York City]]\n\nTilden retired in the early 1880s, living as a near-recluse at his {{convert|110|acre|km2|adj=on}} estate, Greystone, in [[Yonkers, New York|Yonkers]], New York. He died a [[bachelor]] at Greystone on August 4, 1886. He is buried at Cemetery of the Evergreens in [[New Lebanon, New York|New Lebanon]], [[Columbia County, New York]].<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101677|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument|date=December 2005|accessdate=July 3, 2010 |author=Kristin Gibbons and William E. Krattinger|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}}</ref> In reference to the 1876 election, Tilden's gravestone bears the words, \"I Still Trust The People\".<ref>Morris (2003), p. 256</ref>\n\nOf his fortune, estimated at $7&nbsp;million (over $190&nbsp;million in 2016), $4&nbsp;million (over $108&nbsp;million in 2016) was bequeathed for the establishment and maintenance of a free public library and reading-room in the City of New York; but, as the [[Will of Samuel J. Tilden|will]] was successfully contested by relatives, only about $3&nbsp;million (over $81&nbsp;million in 2014) was applied to its original purpose. In 1895, the [[Tilden Trust]] was combined with the [[Astor Library|Astor]] and [[Lenox Library (New York City)|Lenox]] libraries to found the [[New York Public Library]], and the building bears his name on its front.<ref>New York Public Library, [https://www.nypl.org/about/locations/schwarzman \"About the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building\"]; and ''Vol 1, New York City Guide'' (NY: Best Books, 1939), 328-30. {{ISBN|1623760550}}, 9781623760557</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nThe [[Samuel J. Tilden House]] at 15 [[Gramercy Park]] South, which he owned from 1860 until his death, is now used by the [[National Arts Club]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyc-architecture.com/GRP/GRP004.htm |title=National Arts Club |website=NYC-architecture.com |publisher=Tom Fletcher |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> Tilden's Graystone property is now known as [[Untermyer Park]]; it was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1974.<ref name=\"nris\"/> Several places have been named for Tilden, including [[Tilden, Wisconsin]],<ref>{{cite web| title=Home Page| url=http://www.townoftilden.com/| publisher=Town of Tilden| accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Tilden, Nebraska]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.antelopecountymuseum.org/tilden.html |title=History of Tilden, Nebraska |website=Antelope County Museum.org |publisher=Antelope County Historical Society |location=Neligh, NE |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> [[Tilden, Texas]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hlt18 |title=Tilden, Texas |last=Leffler |first=John |date= |website=TSHA Online.org |publisher=Texas State Historical Association |location=Austin, TX |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> [[Tilden Township, Berks County, Pennsylvania|Tilden Township]], Pennsylvania,<ref>{{cite web| title=History| url=http://www.tildentownship.com/history.html| publisher=Tilden Township| accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Grove Park-Tilden Township, Polk County, Minnesota]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Upham |first=Warren |date=1920 |title=Minnesota Geographic Names: Their Origin and Significance |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z4g1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA427 |location=Saint Paul, MN |publisher=Minnesota Historical Society |page=427 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> and [[Tilden, Illinois]]. The [[Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument]] was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2006.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> Other things named for Tilden include [[Samuel J. Tilden High School]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museumoffamilyhistory.com/sths.htm |title=Samuel J. Tilden High School |website=The Museum of Family History |publisher=Steven Lasky |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> [[Fort Tilden]], New York,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nps.gov/gate/learn/historyculture/detailedforttilden.htm |title=A Detailed History of Fort Tilden |website=NPS.gov |publisher=National Park Service |location=Washington, DC |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Root-Tilden Scholarship|Root-Tilden-Kern Scholarship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.nyu.edu/financialaid/jdscholarships/rootscholarship |title=Root-Tilden-Kern Public Interest Scholarships |last=NYU Law School Public Interest Law Center |date=2017 |website=NYU Law School Financial Aid |publisher=New York University Law School |location=New York, NY |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Secondary sources===\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|authorlink1=Thomas J. Archdeacon |last1=Archdeacon |first1=Thomas J. |title=The Erie Canal Ring, Samuel J. Tilden, and the Democratic Party |journal=New York History |date=1978 |volume=59 |issue=4 |pages=408\u2013429 |jstor=23170015}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bigelow |first1=John |editor1-last=Oldaker |editor1-first=Nikki |title=The Life of Samuel J. Tilden |date=2009 |publisher=Show Biz East Productions |isbn=978-0978669812 |edition=Revised|orig-year=1895}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Clancy\n  | first = Herbert J.\n  | year = 1958\n  | title = The Presidential Election of 1880\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/presidentialelec0000clan\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = Loyola University Press\n  | isbn = 978-1-258-19190-0\n  }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Earle |first1=Jonathan Halperin |title=Jacksonian Antislavery and the Politics of Free Soil, 1824-1854 |date=2004 |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |isbn=9780807855553}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Flick |first1=Alexander C. |title=Samuel J. Tilden: A Study in Political Sagacity |date=1939 |publisher=Kennikat Press |OCLC=673301}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Guenther |first1=Karen |title=Potter Committee Investigation of the Disputed Election of 1876 |journal=The Florida Historical Quarterly |date=1983 |volume=61 |issue=3 |pages=281\u2013295 |jstor=30149125}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Hirsch |first1=Mark D. |title=Samuel J. Tilden: The Story of a Lost Opportunity |journal=The American Historical Review |date=1951 |volume=56 |issue=4 |pages=788\u2013802 |doi=10.2307/1851984 |jstor=1851984}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Holt |first1=Michael F. |title=By One Vote: The Disputed Presidential Election of 1876 |date=2008 |publisher=University Press of Kansas |isbn=9780700616084}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Kahn |first1=David |title=The Codebreakers: The Comprehensive History of Secret Communication from Ancient Times to the Internet |date=1996 |publisher=Scribner| edition=Revised|isbn=978-0684831305}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Kelley |first1=Robert |title=The Thought and Character of Samuel J. Tilden: The Democrat As Inheritor |journal=The Historian |date=1964 |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=176-205 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-6563.1964.tb00244.x}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Morris |first1=Roy |title=Fraud of the Century: Rutherford B. Hayes, Samuel Tilden, and the Stolen Election of 1876 |date=2003 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=0-7432-2386-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/fraudofcenturyru00morr }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Polakoff |first1=Keith Ian |title=The Politics of Inertia: The Election of 1876 and the End of Reconstruction |url=https://archive.org/details/politicsofinerti0000pola |url-access=registration |date=1973 |publisher=Louisiana State University Press |isbn=978-0807102107}}\n* Quigley, David. ''Second Founding: New York City, Reconstruction, and the Making of American Democracy''. Hill and Wang (2004) {{ISBN|978-0-8090-8513-2}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Robinson |first1=Lloyd |title=The Stolen Election: Hayes Versus Tilden\u20141876 |date=2001 |publisher=Forge Books |isbn=978-0765302069 |url=https://archive.org/details/stolenelectionha0000robi }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Severn |first1=Bill |title=Samuel J. Tilden and the Stolen Election |url=https://archive.org/details/samueljtilden00seve |url-access=registration |date=1968 |publisher=I. Washburn |OCLC=448909}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Rehnquist |first1=William |title=Centennial Crisis: The Disputed Election of 1876 |date=2004 |publisher=Knopf |isbn=978-0375413872 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/centennialcrisis00rehn }}\n* {{cite book |last1=White |first1=Richard |title=The Republic for which it Stands: The United States During Reconstruction and the Gilded Age, 1865-1896 |date=2017 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199735815}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n===Primary sources===\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n* ''Letters and Literary Memorials of Samuel J. Tilden''. Edited by John Bigelow. Volume I (1908) [https://books.google.com/books?vid=LCCN08004918&id=pgQwDEUl4GgC&printsec=titlepage online edition]\n* ''Letters and Literary Memorials of Samuel J. Tilden''. Edited by John Bigelow. Volume II (1908) [https://books.google.com/books?vid=LCCN08004918&id=No4R1i-_8usC&printsec=titlepage online edition]\n* ''The Writings and Speeches of Samuel J. Tilden''. Edited by John Bigelow. Volume I (1885) [https://books.google.com/books?id=n8HS3Xc84IEC&vid=LCCN09028977&jtp=i online edition]\n* ''The Writings and Speeches of Samuel J. Tilden''. Edited by John Bigelow. Volume II (1885) [https://books.google.com/books?id=_hy2JFcW9v8C&vid=LCCN09028977&jtp=1 online edition]\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/mss/2993 Samuel J. Tilden papers, 1785\u20131929.] [http://www.nypl.org/mss Manuscripts and Archives Division], [http://www.nypl.org New York Public Library]\n* [http://www.samueltilden.com Samuel Tilden.com]\n* [http://www.historyhouse.com/uts/tilden_hayes/ Hayes-Tilden election described in detail, compared to Bush-Gore election]\n* {{Find a Grave|1036|Samuel Jones Tilden}}\n* {{Wikisource-inline|list=\n** {{Cite AmCyc|wstitle=Tilden, Samuel Jones |year=1879 |short=x |noicon=1}}\n** {{Cite EB9|wstitle=Tilden, Samuel Jones |volume=23 |short=x |noicon=1}}\n** {{Cite NIE|wstitle=Tilden, Samuel Jones |year=1905 |short=x  |noicon=1}}\n** {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Tilden, Samuel Jones |short=x |noicon=1}}\n** {{Cite Americana|wstitle=Tilden, Samuel Jones |year=1920 |short=x |noicon=1}}\n}}\n* {{Gutenberg author|id=44199}}\n\n* [http://www.SamuelTilden.com Nikki Oldaker with John Bigelow, 2006, ''Samuel Tilden the Real 19th President (film)'']\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=Leander Buck}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[New York State Assembly|New York Assembly]]<br>from [[Manhattan|New York County]]'s 18th district|years=1872}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Biglin Brothers|Barney Biglin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Francis Kernan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]|years=[[New York state election, 1874|1874]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucius Robinson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dean Richmond]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[New York State Democratic Committee|New York Democratic Party]]|years=1866\u20131874}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Allen C. Beach]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Horace Greeley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[List of United States Democratic Party presidential tickets|nominee]] for [[President of the United States]]|years=[[1876 United States presidential election|1876]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Winfield Scott Hancock]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Adams Dix]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]|years=1875\u20131876}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucius Robinson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Unsuccessful major party pres candidates}}\n{{USDemPresNominees}}\n{{Governors of New York}}\n{{New York State Democratic Committee}}\n{{United States presidential election, 1876}}\n{{United States presidential election, 1880}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tilden, Samuel J.}}\n[[Category:1814 births]]\n[[Category:1886 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Free Soilers]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People from New Lebanon, New York]]\n[[Category:Tylden family]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1876 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Gramercy Park]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|19th-century American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Samuel Tilden\n|image        = SamuelJonesTilden.jpg\n|order        = 25th [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]\n|lieutenant   = [[William Dorsheimer]]\n|term_start   = January 1, 1875\n|term_end     = December 31, 1876\n|predecessor  = [[John Adams Dix]]\n|successor    = [[Lucius Robinson]]\n|office1      = Member of the [[New York State Assembly]]<br>from [[Manhattan|New York County]]'s 18th district\n|term_start1  = January 1, 1872\n|term_end1    = December 31, 1872\n|predecessor1 = Leander Buck\n|successor1   = [[Biglin Brothers|Barney Biglin]]\n|office2      = Chair of the [[New York State Democratic Committee|New York Democratic Party]]\n|term_start2  = August 1866\n|term_end2    = September 1874\n|predecessor2 = [[Dean Richmond]]\n|successor2   = [[Allen C. Beach]]\n|office3      = Member of the New York State Assembly from [[Manhattan|New York County]]\n|alongside3   = 13 others<br/>(Multi-member district)\n|term_start3  = 1846\n|term_end3    = 1847\n|predecessor3 = Various (Multi-member district)\n|successor3   = Various (Multi-member district)\n|office4      = [[New York City Law Department|Corporation Counsel]] of [[New York City]]\n|term_start4  = 1843\n|term_end4    = 1844\n|predecessor4 = Alexander W. Bradford\n|successor4   = Stephen Sammons\n|birth_name   = Samuel Jones Tilden\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1814|2|9}}\n|birth_place  = [[New Lebanon, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1886|8|4|1814|2|9}}\n|death_place  = [[Yonkers, New York]], U.S.\n|restingplace = [[Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument]], Cemetery of the Evergreens, New Lebanon, New York\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[Yale University]]<br>[[New York University]]\n|signature    = Samuel Tilden Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Samuel Jones Tilden ''' (February 9, 1814 \u2013 August 4, 1886) was the 25th [[Governor of New York]] and the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] candidate for president in the [[1876 United States presidential election|disputed election of 1876]]. As of 2020, Tilden is the only individual to [[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|win an outright majority of the popular vote]] in a [[United States presidential election]] but lose the election.{{efn|As of 2020, four candidates have lost a presidential election despite garnering a [[plurality (voting)|plurality]] of the popular vote; [[Andrew Jackson]] in [[1824 United States presidential election|1824]]; [[Grover Cleveland]] in [[1888 United States presidential election|1888]]; [[Al Gore]] in [[2000 United States presidential election|2000]]; and [[Hillary Clinton]] in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kernell |first1=Samuel |last2=Jacobson |first2=Gary C. |last3=Kousser |first3=Thad |last4=Vavreck |first4=Lynn |date=2020 |title=The Logic of American Politics |edition=Ninth |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vKR0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA507 |location=Thousand Oaks, CA |publisher=CQ Press |page=507 |isbn=978-1-5443-2301-5 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>}} \n\nTilden was born into a wealthy family in [[New Lebanon, New York]]. Attracted to politics at a young age, he became a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Martin Van Buren]], the eighth [[President of the United States]]. After studying at [[Yale University]] and [[New York University School of Law]], Tilden began a legal career in [[New York City]], becoming a noted corporate lawyer. He served in the [[New York State Assembly]] and helped launch Van Buren's [[third party (United States)|third party]], anti-[[slavery in the United States|slavery]] candidacy in the [[1848 United States presidential election|1848 presidential election]]. Though he opposed the election of [[Abraham Lincoln]] in 1860, Tilden supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] during the [[American Civil War]]. After the Civil War, Tilden was selected as the chairman of the [[New York State Democratic Committee]], and he managed Democratic nominee [[Horatio Seymour]]'s campaign in the [[1868 United States presidential election|1868 presidential election]]. \n\nTilden initially cooperated with the state party's [[Tammany Hall]] faction, but he broke with them in 1871 due to boss [[William M. Tweed]]'s rampant corruption. Tilden won election as [[Governor of New York]] in 1874, and in that office he helped break up the \"[[Canal Ring (New York)|Canal Ring]].\" Tilden's battle against public corruption, along with his personal fortune and electoral success in the country's most populous state, made him the leading candidate for the Democratic nomination for president in 1876. Tilden was selected as the nominee on the second ballot of the [[1876 Democratic National Convention]]. In the general election, Tilden faced [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Rutherford B. Hayes]], another governor with reform credentials. Tilden focused his campaign on civil service reform, support for the [[gold standard]], and opposition to high taxes, but many of his supporters were more concerned with ending [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] in the South.\n\nMost observers initially believed that Tilden had won the election, but disputes in four states left both Tilden and Hayes without a majority of the [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral vote]]. As Tilden had won 184 electoral votes, one vote shy of a majority, a Hayes victory required that he sweep all of the disputed electoral votes. Against Tilden's wishes, Congress appointed the bipartisan [[Electoral Commission (United States)|Electoral Commission]] to settle the controversy. Republicans had a one-seat advantage on the Electoral Commission, and in a series of party-line rulings, ruled that Hayes had won all of the disputed electoral votes. In the [[Compromise of 1877]], Democratic leaders agreed to accept Hayes as the victor in return for the end of Reconstruction. Tilden was a major contender for the Democratic presidential nomination in the [[1880 United States presidential election|1880]] and [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential elections]], but declined to run.\n\n== Early life ==\n[[Image:SamuelJTilden.jpeg|thumb|Samuel Tilden as a young man]]\n\nTilden was born in [[New Lebanon, New York]], the youngest son of Elam Tilden and Polly Jones Tilden.<ref>Bigelow (2009), pp. 12\u201315</ref> He was descended from [[Tylden (family)|Nathaniel Tilden]], an early [[English people|English]] settler who came to [[North America]] in 1634. His father and other family members were the makers of [[Tilden's Extract]], a popular [[patent medicine]] of the 1800s and early 1900s derived from [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]].<ref>William Lee Richter, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cyGb-eMnmXkC&pg=PA610 ''Historical Dictionary of the Civil War and Reconstruction''], 2004, page 610</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=psbmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA117 Obituary, Samuel J. Tilden (nephew of New York Governor)], ''The Pharmaceutical Era'', March 1914, p. 117</ref> Tilden's father maintained relationships with many influential politicians, including President [[Martin Van Buren]], who became Tilden's political idol.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 85</ref> Tilden was frequently in poor health during his youth, and he spent much of his time studying politics and reading works such as ''[[The Wealth of Nations]]''.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 85</ref> Tilden's health troubles prevented him from regularly attending school, and he dropped out of [[Yale University]] after a single term.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 84\u201386</ref>\n\nLikely motivated by a family friendship with [[Benjamin Franklin Butler (lawyer)|Benjamin Franklin Butler]], then serving as a professor at [[New York University School of Law]], Tilden enrolled there to resume his studies, and he continued to attend intermittently from 1838 to 1841.<ref>{{cite book|title=The life and public services of Hon. Samuel J. Tilden: Democratic nominee ...|author=Theodore Pease Cook|page=9}}</ref> While studying at NYU, Tilden also [[reading law|read law]] in the office of attorney [[John W. Edmonds]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Scharf |first=John Thomas |date=1886 |title=History of Westchester County, New York |volume=Volume 1, Part 2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EkgVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA504 |location=Philadelphia, PA |publisher=L. E. Preston & Co. |page=554 |ref={{sfnRef|''History of Westchester County, New York''}}}}</ref> He was admitted to the bar in 1841 and became a skilled [[corporate lawyer]].{{sfn|''History of Westchester County, New York''|page=554}} Tilden affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], and he frequently campaigned on behalf of Van Buren and other Democratic candidates.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 86\u201389</ref>\n\n== Early political career ==\n[[File:MVanBuren.png|thumb|upright=0.9|Tilden was a protege of [[Martin Van Buren]], the 8th [[President of the United States]].]]\n\nIn 1843, as a reward for campaign work on behalf of Governor [[William C. Bouck]], Tilden was appointed as New York City's corporation counsel.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 89</ref> Tilden handled hundreds of cases on behalf of the city, but was forced out of office in 1844 after New York City elected a [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] mayor.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 90</ref> He served as a delegate to the [[1844 Democratic National Convention]], which rejected Van Buren and nominated [[James K. Polk]] for president.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 90</ref> At the urging of Governor [[Silas Wright]], Tilden won election to the [[New York State Assembly]].<ref>Morris (2003), p. 91</ref> He became a key ally to Wright and helped end the [[Anti-Rent War]] by passing a compromise land bill that defused tensions between tenant farmers and their landlords.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 91\u201392</ref> After serving as a delegate to the 1846 [[New York State Constitutional Convention]], Tilden left public office to focus on his legal practice, where he gained a national reputation as a \"financial physician\" for struggling railroads.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 89\u201393</ref> Tilden's successful legal practice, combined with shrewd investments, made him rich.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kessner |first=Thomas |date=2003 |title=Capital City: New York City and the Men Behind America's Rise to Economic |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PefKIplMWrUC&pg=PA185 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Simon & Schuster |page=185 |isbn=978-0-7432-5753-4 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> His success at money management and investing caused many of his friends, relatives, and political allies, including Van Buren, to allow Tilden to manage their finances.<ref>Severn (1968), p. 64</ref>\n\nTilden helped to found the \"[[Barnburner]]s\", an anti-[[slavery in the United States|slavery]] faction of the New York Democratic Party that arose in the midst of the debate over the [[Wilmot Proviso]]. Like other Barnburners, Tilden sought to prevent the spread of slavery into the [[Mexican cession|land acquired from Mexico]] in the [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo]]. He helped organize the 1848 [[Free Soil Party|Free Soil]] Convention, which nominated Van Buren for president. Van Buren's candidacy in the [[1848 United States presidential election|1848 presidential election]] may have played a role in the victory of Whig nominee [[Zachary Taylor]] over Democratic nominee [[Lewis Cass]]. Unlike many other anti-slavery Democrats, Tilden did not join the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] in the 1850s, but he did not have close relations with Democratic presidents [[Franklin Pierce]] and [[James Buchanan]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 94\u201395</ref> In [[New York state election, 1855|1855]], Tilden was the unsuccessful [[New York State Attorney General|state attorney general]] candidate of the \"[[Hunkers and Barnburners|Soft]]\" faction of Barnburners, which favored compromise and reconciliation with the Democratic Party.<ref>Robinson (2001), p. 85</ref> In [[New York state election, 1859|1859]], after he lost an election to serve as New York City's corporation counsel, Tilden announced that he was \"out of politics.\"<ref>Morris (2003), p. 95</ref>\n\nIn the [[1860 United States presidential election|1860 presidential election]], Tilden strongly opposed the candidacy of Republican presidential nominee [[Abraham Lincoln]]. He warned that the election of Lincoln could lead to the secession of the South and a subsequent civil war.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 95\u201396</ref> Tilden initially opposed using force to prevent secession, but he supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] after the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]]. Tilden served as the manager of [[Horatio Seymour]]'s successful 1862 campaign for governor, and played a key role in securing the nomination of [[George B. McClellan]] at the [[1864 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 96\u201397</ref>\n\nIn 1867, Tilden received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from [[New York University]].<ref>{{cite book |last=General Alumni Society, New York University |date=1906 |title=General Alumni Catalogue |url=https://archive.org/details/generalalumnica01univgoog |location=New York, NY |publisher=New York University |page=170}}</ref> He was also chosen as a delegate to that year's [[New York Constitution#Constitutional Convention of 1867\u20131868|state constitutional convention]].<ref>{{cite news |date=June 4, 1867 |title=The Constitutional Convention to Assemble To-Day |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/329585675/ |work=[[New York Herald]] |location=New York, NY |url-access=subscription |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |page=7}}</ref>\n\n== State party leader ==\n[[File:SamuelTilden.png|thumb|right|upright|A portrait of Samuel Jones Tilden]]\n\nFollowing the end of the Civil War, Tilden won election as the chairman of the [[New York State Democratic Committee]]. He served as Seymour's campaign chairman in the [[1868 United States presidential election|1868 presidential election]], but Seymour lost the election to Republican nominee [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 97\u201398</ref> After the election, Tilden broke with [[William M. Tweed]], the leader of the [[Tammany Hall]] [[political machine]]. Through bribery, patronage, and control of [[Irish-American]] voters, Tweed and his allies had become the dominant power in both New York City and the state of New York.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 99\u2013102</ref> In 1871, former Tammany associate [[James O'Brien (U.S. Congressman)|James O'Brien]] leaked Tweed's account books to the ''[[New York Times]]''. The ''Times'' subsequently began a public crusade against Tammany Hall, and Tilden launched an investigation into Tweed's bank records. Tilden ran for the New York State Assembly as part of a slate of anti-Tammany Democrats; at the state party convention, he declared that it was \"time to proclaim that whoever plunders the people, though he steal the livery of heaven to serve the devil in, is no Democrat.\" The anti-Tammany Democrats, including Tilden, won a major victory in the [[New York state election, 1871|1871 state elections]], and Tweed was indicted on 120 counts of fraud and other violations. After the election, Tweed fled the state, but he was eventually extradited back to New York, where he died in prison in 1878.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nTilden's role in taking down Tweed bolstered his popularity, and he was elected Governor of New York in [[New York state election, 1874|1874]]. As governor, he continued to focus on rooting out corruption. He helped to break up the \"[[Canal Ring (New York)|Canal Ring]],\" a bipartisan group of state and local officials who had enriched themselves by overcharging for the maintenance of the [[New York State Canal System]]. Tilden gained a national reputation as a reform governor, a valuable asset given the number of [[Grant administration scandals|scandals]] that had come into public view during the [[presidency of Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 104\u2013105</ref>\n\nIn 1875, Tilden received an honorary LL.D. from [[Yale University]].<ref name=Yale_Catalogue>{{cite book |last=Yale University |date=1877 |title=Catalogue of the Officers and Graduates of Yale University |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=UahGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA51 |location=New Haven, CT |publisher=Morehouse and Taylor |page=51}}</ref> At the same time, Yale also enrolled him as a graduate of the Class of 1837 and he received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree.<ref name=\"Yale_Catalogue\"/>\n\n==Presidential election of 1876==\n{{See also|Samuel Tilden presidential campaign, 1876}}\n\n===Democratic nomination===\n[[Image:Tilden and Hendricks campaign poster.jpg|thumb|Campaign poster for the election of 1876]]\n\nBy the time of the June [[1876 Democratic National Convention]], Tilden had emerged as the front-runner for the Democratic nomination in the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 presidential election]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 106</ref> Tilden's appeal to the national party was based on his reputation for reform and his electoral success in the country's most populous state. He was also a skilled organizer whose canvassing system and field knowledge was so thorough that, months before the 1874 election, he'd predicted his own winning margin accurately to within 300 votes.<ref>Holt (2008), p. 100</ref> Tilden further bolstered his presidential candidacy through a nationwide newspaper advertising campaign. As many Democrats expected that their party would win the 1876 presidential elections, Tilden faced competition from some of the party's most prominent leaders, including [[Thomas F. Bayard]], [[Allen G. Thurman]], [[Thomas A. Hendricks]], and General [[Winfield Scott Hancock]].<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 106\u2013107</ref>\n\nDuring the difficult economic times of the [[Panic of 1873]], the major ideological divide in the Democratic Party concerned the issue of [[History of monetary policy in the United States|currency]]. Many \"soft money\" Democrats wanted Congress to repeal the [[Specie Payment Resumption Act]] and authorize the printing of more [[greenback (money)|greenback]]s, [[banknotes]] that had first been printed during the Civil War. The printing of more greenbacks would result in [[inflation]] and potentially benefit farmers by raising prices and helping them pay down their debts. Like most Republicans and \"hard money\" members of the conservative business establishment, Tilden believed that the termination of greenback circulation (which would return the country to the [[gold standard]]) was the best way to solve the ongoing economic crisis. Tilden's lieutenants at the Democratic National Convention emphasized Tilden's reform credentials above all else, but they also ensured that the party platform endorsed Tilden's hard money views.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 108\u2013109, 112\u2013114</ref> \n\nTilden won a majority of the votes cast on the first presidential ballot of the convention, but fell short of the two-thirds majority required to win the Democratic presidential nomination. His closest rival was Hendricks, who had the support of New York party boss [[John Kelly (New York politician)|John Kelly]] and the soft money faction of Democrats. Tilden won the necessary two-thirds majority on the second presidential ballot, and the convention then voted to make his nomination unanimous. Delegates unanimously chose Hendricks as Tilden's running mate, providing a balance between the hard money and soft money factions.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 115\u2013117</ref> Though the Republicans had nominated a ticket led by [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] of Ohio, another governor who had established a reputation for honest governance, Tilden was widely regarded as the favorite in the general election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 80\u201383, 122</ref>\n\n===General election===\n[[File:1876 U.S. presidential election, contested states.png|thumb|upright=1.5|In the aftermath of the [[1876 United States presidential election|1876 presidential election]], the electoral votes of four states were disputed.]]\n\nPer tradition, both Tilden and Hayes avoided publicly campaigning for president, leaving that task to their supporters; Tilden appointed [[Abram Hewitt]] to lead his campaign.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 123, 131\u2013132</ref> The Republican campaign established a major cash advantage, partly because Tilden refused to contribute much of his personal fortune to the campaign.<ref>Morris (2003), p. 121</ref> The Democrats campaigned on the theme of \"retrenchment and reform\" and attacked the \"corrupt centralism\" of the Grant administration.<ref name=\"morris118120\"/> Tilden blamed high taxes and the Grant administration for the economic downturn, and, like Hayes, promised [[U.S. Civil Service Reform|civil service reform]] and hard money policies.<ref>White (2017), pp. 328\u2013330</ref> Republicans, meanwhile, focused on their party's identification with Lincoln and the Union cause in the Civil War; many Republicans still associated the Democratic Party with slavery and disunion.<ref name=\"morris118120\">Morris (2003), pp. 118\u2013120</ref> Rebutting Republican charges, Tilden categorically denied that he had any intention of compensating the South for any slaves emancipated or losses suffered during the Civil War.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 161\u2013162</ref> For their part, many Democrats cared little for Tilden's emphasis on reform, and were instead focused on ending sixteen years of Republican leadership. Southern Democrats especially hoped to end [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] and gain control of South Carolina, Florida, and Louisiana, the last three \"[[Redeemers|unredeemed]]\" Southern states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 125\u2013126, 146</ref> Southern whites, who overwhelmingly favored Tilden, used violence and intimidation to suppress the turnout of Republican-leaning [[African-American]] voters.<ref>White (2017), pp. 330\u2013331</ref> Tilden worked to distance himself from violent encounters like the [[Hamburg massacre]], in which disgruntled Southern whites clashed with the Republican-led government of South Carolina.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 129\u2013131</ref>\n\nBoth campaigns considered New York, Ohio, and Indiana to be the key [[swing states]], but the campaigns also focused on several smaller states, including the three unredeemed Southern states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 155\u2013156</ref> Ultimately, Hayes swept the West and won much of the North, but Tilden carried the closely contested Northern states of New York, New Jersey, Indiana, and Connecticut, swept the [[border states (American Civil War)|border states]], and carried most of the South. He had won a majority of the popular vote and tallied clear victories in seventeen states, leaving him one [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral vote]] short of a majority. On November 6, the day after election day, most major newspapers reported that Tilden had won the election; however, Hayes still had a narrow path to victory if he could sweep the electoral votes of Florida, South Carolina, and Louisiana.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 164\u2013166</ref> Hayes refused to formally concede, but told members of the press that he was \"of the opinion that the Democrats have carried the country and elected Tilden.\"<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 167\u2013171</ref> Tilden, meanwhile, urged his alarmed followers, many of whom believed that the Republicans were attempting to steal the election, to remain calm and refrain from violence. Both parties feared the possibility that a dispute over the election would lead to armed conflict; Tilden discussed appointing General [[George B. McClellan]] as his military assistant, while President Grant ordered army and naval units to reinforce Washington.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 172\u2013174</ref>\n\n===Post-election controversy===\n[[Image:SJTilden of NY.jpg|thumb|right|Samuel Jones Tilden]]\n\nWith the election in doubt, each party sent some of their most prominent leaders to monitor the election process in the three disputed Southern states. Initial election returns showed that Hayes had carried South Carolina by several hundred votes, but that Tilden had won Florida by 91 votes and Louisiana by over 6000 votes. Republicans controlled the bodies charged with determining the validity of election results in all three states.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 174\u2013178</ref> On November 22, the South Carolina canvassing board adjourned after declaring that Hayes had won the state's electoral votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 180\u2013182</ref> On December 4, the Louisiana canvassing board announced that it had thrown out 15,623 votes due to \"systemic intimidation,\" leaving Hayes as the winner of all of the state's electoral votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 191\u2013192</ref> Early on the morning of December 6, the day the Electoral College was scheduled to convene, the Florida canvassing board announced that Hayes had won the state by a margin of 924 votes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 193\u2013197</ref> Democrats challenged the results in all three contested Southern states. Meanwhile, another controversy had arisen in Oregon, where a Hayes elector, John Watts, resigned because his simultaneous service as a presidential elector and as a low-ranking official in the [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office]] violated the [[United States Constitution]]. After Watts resigned, the state's Democratic governor appointed an elector to fill the vacancy, while, separately, the state's two remaining Hayes electors chose a third elector to fill the vacancy caused by Watts's resignation.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 183\u2013185, 197\u2013198</ref>\n\nOn December 6, the members of the Electoral College met in Washington, D.C., but the disputes in four states prevented a conclusive vote for president.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 197\u2013198</ref> With the Electoral College unable to select a president, the disputed election became an issue for Congress to settle; Republicans controlled the Senate, while Democrats controlled the House. The vague wording of the Constitution gave rise to further controversy, as Republicans held that [[Thomas W. Ferry]], a Republican senator from Michigan and the [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|president pro tempore]] of the [[United States Senate]], could determine the validity of the disputed electoral votes. Democrats argued that Ferry could only count the votes that were not disputed; in such a scenario, neither candidate would have an electoral vote majority, necessitating a [[contingent election]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. Since Democrats controlled a majority of the state delegations in the House, they would be able to elect Tilden as president in a contingent election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 200\u2013201</ref> In response to the controversy, Tilden compiled his own study of electoral procedures in the previous 22 presidential elections. He delivered the study to every sitting member of Congress, but congressional Republicans were not swayed by Tilden's argument that history supported the Democratic position on the election returns.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 203\u2013204</ref> He continued to call for calm, and rejected Abram Hewitt's suggestion that he ask his supporters to engage in mass public demonstrations.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 206\u2013207, 214</ref>\n\n===Electoral Commission===\n[[File:President Rutherford Hayes 1870 - 1880 Restored.jpg|thumb|upright=1|[[Rutherford B. Hayes]] defeated Tilden in the 1876 election.]]\n\nOn January 26, both houses of Congress agreed to establish the 15-member [[Electoral Commission (United States)|Electoral Commission]] to settle the dispute over the contested electoral votes. The commission consisted of five Democratic members of Congress, five Republican members of Congress, and five justices of the [[Supreme Court of the United States]]. Of the Supreme Court justices, two were to be Democrats, two were to be Republicans, and the fifth justice would be selected by the other four justices. Tilden opposed the creation of the Electoral Commission because he still hoped to force a contingent election in the House of Representatives, but he was unable to prevent Democratic congressmen from voting for the establishment of the commission. Most had expected that the fifth justice on the commission would be Associate Justice [[David Davis (Supreme Court justice)|David Davis]], a [[political independent]], but Davis refused to serve on the commission after he accepted election to the Senate. Another associate justice, Republican [[Joseph P. Bradley]], was instead chosen as the fifth justice on the Electoral Commission.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 216\u2013219</ref> In a series of 8-to-7, party-line decisions, the Electoral Commission voted to award all of the contested electoral votes to Hayes.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 222\u2013235</ref>\n\nEven after the Electoral Commission delivered its rulings, the House of Representatives could have blocked the inauguration of Hayes by refusing to certify the election results.<ref>White (2017), p. 332</ref> Though some House Democrats hoped to do just that, they were unable to prevent the House of Representatives from blocking certification, as many House Democrats joined with their Republican colleagues in accepting the results.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 235\u2013236</ref> During the proceedings of the Electoral Commission, high-ranking members of both parties had discussed the possibility of declaring Hayes the winner in exchange for the removal of all federal troops from the South. The [[Compromise of 1877]], as it became known, may have played a role in preventing the House from challenging the Electoral Commission's rulings, although author Roy Morris, Jr. argues that the compromise \"was more a mutual concession of the obvious than a device for controlling larger events.\"<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 232\u2013234</ref> Some other historians, including [[C. Vann Woodward]], have argued that the Compromise of 1877 played the decisive role in determining the outcome of the election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kleinfeld |first1=N. R. |title=COUNTING THE VOTE: THE HISTORY; President Tilden? No, but Almost, in Another Vote That Dragged On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/12/us/counting-vote-history-president-tilden-no-but-almost-another-vote-that-dragged.html |accessdate=6 November 2018 |newspaper=New York Times |date=12 November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Review: NOT A COMPROMISE |journal=The Review of Politics |date=2009 |volume=71 |issue=4 |pages=698\u2013700 |jstor=25655882}}</ref> On March 2, two days before the end of Grant's term, Congress declared Hayes the victor of the 1876 presidential election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 237\u2013238</ref> Hayes took office on March 4, and withdrew the last federal soldiers from the South in April 1877, bringing an end to the Reconstruction Era.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 240, 244\u2013245</ref>\n\nSome Democrats urged Tilden to reject the results and take the presidential [[oath of office]], but Tilden declined to do so. On March 3, the House passed a resolution declaring Tilden the \"duly elected President of the United States,\" but this had no legal effect.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 241\u2013242</ref> Tilden himself stated that, \"I can retire to private life with the consciousness that I shall receive from posterity the credit of having been elected to the highest position in the gift of the people, without any of the cares and responsibilities of the office.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=King |first=Gilbert |date=September 7, 2012 |title=The Ugliest, Most Contentious Presidential Election Ever |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/the-ugliest-most-contentious-presidential-election-ever-28429530/ |magazine=Smithsonian Magazine |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Smithsonian Institution}}</ref> Tilden was the second individual, after [[Andrew Jackson]] in 1824, to lose a presidential election [[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|despite winning at least a plurality of the popular vote]].<ref name=\"Revesz\">{{cite news |last1=Revesz |first1=Rachel |title=Five presidential nominees who won popular vote but lost the election |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/popular-vote-electoral-college-five-presidential-nominees-hillary-clinton-al-gore-a7420971.html |accessdate=6 November 2018 |newspaper=The Independent |date=16 November 2016}}</ref>[[Grover Cleveland]] (1888), [[Al Gore]] (2000), and [[Hillary Clinton]] (2016) subsequently won pluralities while losing the electoral vote.<ref name=\"Revesz\"/> Tilden remains the only individual to lose a presidential election while winning an outright majority of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Law |first=Tara |date=May 15, 2019 |title=These Presidents Won the Electoral College \u2014 But Not the Popular Vote |url=https://time.com/5579161/presidents-elected-electoral-college/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |location=New York, NY |publisher=Time USA, LLC}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n===Potter Committee===\n[[Image:STilden.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Samuel Tilden]]\n\nIn 1878, Democratic Congressman [[Clarkson Nott Potter]] convinced the House of Representatives to create a committee to investigate allegations of fraud and corruption in the 1876 election. Potter was appointed as the head of the commission, which Democrats hoped would implicate Hayes and damage the Republican Party in the next presidential election.<ref>Guenther (1983), 284\u2013285</ref> Rather than produce conclusive evidence of Republican malfeasance, the committee uncovered conflicting evidence that reflected poorly on election and campaign officials of both parties. For ten months beginning in May 1878, the Potter Committee subpoenaed all telegrams sent by political operatives during the election dispute. 29,275 telegrams had been sent, but all save 641 had been routinely destroyed by [[Western Union]]. The remaining telegrams were in cipher, as was common with business and political communication in the telegraph era. ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' editor [[Whitelaw Reid]] obtained and deciphered many of the telegrams and, in October 1878, he published the story of the Democratic efforts to sway election officials through bribery and other means. The revelation of the bribery attempts undercut the Democratic Party's argument that Tilden had been cheated out of the presidency.<ref>Kahn (1996), pp. 221\u2013229</ref> Tilden was not implicated in any wrongdoing, but the investigation into the Cipher Telegrams damaged his national standing.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 250\u2013251</ref>\n\n===Election of 1880===\n\nAfter the controversy over the election of 1876, Tilden became the presumptive Democratic candidate in [[1880 United States presidential election|1880 presidential election]]. He declined to run for another term as governor in 1879, focusing instead on building support for the 1880 presidential nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), p. 52</ref> The revelations of the Potter Committee, along with Tilden's persistent health issues, both damaged Tilden's national standing, but his superior political organization and personal fortune ensured that he remained a serious contender for the Democratic nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 56\u201357</ref> Tilden's standing with the party slipped further following the Republican victory in the [[New York state election, 1879|New York gubernatorial election in 1879]]. In that election, a revitalized Tammany Hall organization split from the regular Democratic party in a patronage dispute with Tilden's faction.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 61\u201363</ref> In the months before the [[1880 Democratic National Convention]], rumors about Tilden's intentions circulated wildly, but Tilden refused to definitively state whether or not he would seek the Democratic nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 74\u201375</ref>\n\nAs the New York delegation left for the national convention in Cincinnati, Tilden gave a letter to one of his chief supporters, [[Daniel Manning]], suggesting that his health might force him to decline the nomination.<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 122\u2013123</ref> Tilden hoped to be nominated, but only if he was the unanimous choice of the convention; if not, Manning was entrusted to make the contents of Tilden's letter available to the New York delegation.<ref name=\"Goldman\">{{cite book |last=Goldman |first=Andrew |date=2015 |orig-year=1990 |title=The National Party Chairmen and Committees |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e0agDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT107 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Routledge |page=107 |isbn=978-1-3154-9067-0}}</ref> The New York delegation interpreted the letter as a notice of withdrawal, and the delegates began looking for a new candidate, eventually settling on Speaker of the House [[Samuel J. Randall]].<ref>Clancy (1958), pp. 124\u2013126, 139</ref> Ultimately, the party nominated [[Winfield Scott Hancock]], who lost the election to [[James A Garfield]].<ref name=\"Goldman\"/>{{rp|108-109}} Though many Democrats favored Tilden for the party's nomination in the [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential election]], Tilden once again declined to run due to poor health.<ref name=\"Goldman\"/>{{rp|110}} He endorsed New York Governor [[Grover Cleveland]], who won the Democratic nomination and went on to defeat [[James G. Blaine]] in the general election.<ref>Morris (2003), pp. 255\u2013256</ref>\n\n===Retirement and death===\n[[File:Tilden 112 cu jeh.jpg|thumb|Statue in New York City]]\n\nTilden retired in the early 1880s, living as a near-recluse at his {{convert|110|acre|km2|adj=on}} estate, Greystone, in [[Yonkers, New York|Yonkers]], New York. He died a [[bachelor]] at Greystone on August 4, 1886. He is buried at Cemetery of the Evergreens in [[New Lebanon, New York|New Lebanon]], [[Columbia County, New York]].<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=101677|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument|date=December 2005|accessdate=July 3, 2010 |author=Kristin Gibbons and William E. Krattinger|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}}</ref> In reference to the 1876 election, Tilden's gravestone bears the words, \"I Still Trust The People\".<ref>Morris (2003), p. 256</ref>\n\nOf his fortune, estimated at $7&nbsp;million (over $190&nbsp;million in 2016), $4&nbsp;million (over $108&nbsp;million in 2016) was bequeathed for the establishment and maintenance of a free public library and reading-room in the City of New York; but, as the [[Will of Samuel J. Tilden|will]] was successfully contested by relatives, only about $3&nbsp;million (over $81&nbsp;million in 2014) was applied to its original purpose. In 1895, the [[Tilden Trust]] was combined with the [[Astor Library|Astor]] and [[Lenox Library (New York City)|Lenox]] libraries to found the [[New York Public Library]], and the building bears his name on its front.<ref>New York Public Library, [https://www.nypl.org/about/locations/schwarzman \"About the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building\"]; and ''Vol 1, New York City Guide'' (NY: Best Books, 1939), 328-30. {{ISBN|1623760550}}, 9781623760557</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nThe [[Samuel J. Tilden House]] at 15 [[Gramercy Park]] South, which he owned from 1860 until his death, is now used by the [[National Arts Club]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyc-architecture.com/GRP/GRP004.htm |title=National Arts Club |website=NYC-architecture.com |publisher=Tom Fletcher |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> Tilden's Graystone property is now known as [[Untermyer Park]]; it was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1974.<ref name=\"nris\"/> Several places have been named for Tilden, including [[Tilden, Wisconsin]],<ref>{{cite web| title=Home Page| url=http://www.townoftilden.com/| publisher=Town of Tilden| accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Tilden, Nebraska]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.antelopecountymuseum.org/tilden.html |title=History of Tilden, Nebraska |website=Antelope County Museum.org |publisher=Antelope County Historical Society |location=Neligh, NE |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> [[Tilden, Texas]], [[Tilden Township, Berks County, Pennsylvania|Tilden Township]], Pennsylvania,<ref>{{cite web| title=History| url=http://www.tildentownship.com/history.html| publisher=Tilden Township| accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Grove Park-Tilden Township, Polk County, Minnesota]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Upham |first=Warren |date= |title=Minnesota Geographic Names: Their Origin and Significance |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z4g1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA427 |location=Saint Paul, MN |publisher=Minnesota Historical Society |page=427 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> and [[Tilden, Illinois]]. The [[Gov. Samuel J. Tilden Monument]] was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2006.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> Other things named for Tilden include [[Samuel J. Tilden High School]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museumoffamilyhistory.com/sths.htm |title=Samuel J. Tilden High School |website=The Museum of Family History |publisher=Steven Lasky |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> [[Fort Tilden]], New York,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nps.gov/gate/learn/historyculture/detailedforttilden.htm |title=A Detailed History of Fort Tilden |website=NPS.gov |publisher=National Park Service |location=Washington, DC |access-date=April 29, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Root-Tilden Scholarship|Root-Tilden-Kern Scholarship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.nyu.edu/financialaid/jdscholarships/rootscholarship |title=Root-Tilden-Kern Public Interest Scholarships |last=NYU Law School Public Interest Law Center |date=2017 |website=NYU Law School Financial Aid |publisher=New York University Law School |location=New York, NY |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Secondary sources===\n\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|authorlink1=Thomas J. Archdeacon |last1=Archdeacon |first1=Thomas J. |title=The Erie Canal Ring, Samuel J. Tilden, and the Democratic Party |journal=New York History |date=1978 |volume=59 |issue=4 |pages=408\u2013429 |jstor=23170015}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bigelow |first1=John |editor1-last=Oldaker |editor1-first=Nikki |title=The Life of Samuel J. Tilden |date=2009 |publisher=Show Biz East Productions |isbn=978-0978669812 |edition=Revised|orig-year=1895}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Clancy\n  | first = Herbert J.\n  | year = 1958\n  | title = The Presidential Election of 1880\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/presidentialelec0000clan\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = Loyola University Press\n  | isbn = 978-