{"title_page": "Kinan Azmeh", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Kinan Azmeh\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1976|6|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]\n| origin           = Syria\n| instrument       = [[Clarinet]]\n| genre            = [[Jazz fusion]], [[contemporary]]\n| occupation       = musician, composer\n}}\n\n'''Kinan Azmeh''' ({{lang-ar|\u0643\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0638\u0645\u0629|Kin\u0101n Azme}}, born June 10, 1976 in [[Damascus]]), is a [[Syrian]] [[clarinet]] player and composer of [[Contemporary Music|contemporary music]]. Performing with orchestras such as the [[New York Philharmonic]], the [[Seattle Symphony]], the [[Bavarian Radio Symphony Orchestra]], the [[West\u2013Eastern Divan Orchestra|West-Eastern Divan Orchestra]], or the Syrian Symphony Orchestra, he has played both as a [[Solo (music)|soloist]] of classical works as well as of contemporary compositions.\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Damascus]], [[Syria]] in 1976,<ref name=\"incognito\">[http://www.incognito.com.lb/store/node/235 Incognito] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503072702/http://www.incognito.com.lb/store/node/235 |date=2010-05-03 }} page on Azmeh</ref> Azmeh began to play the clarinet at age six. Originally taking lessons on the [[violin]], he switched to an even-handed instrument that left-handed players did not play too differently from right-handed players.<ref name=\"FW\">[http://www.fw-magazine.com/content/kinan-azmeh-i-am-living-example-whatthis-country-has-offer Interview with Azmeh]</ref>  Azmeh studied at the Arab conservatory of music in Damascus. At the [[University of Damascus]], he double-majored in [[electrical engineering]] and music.<ref name=\"epochtimes\">[http://www.theepochtimes.com/news/8-6-8/71470.html Epoch Times] article</ref>  Azmeh received his master's degree and graduate diploma in music from the [[Juilliard School]] in [[New York City]]. In 1997, Azmeh was the first Arab musician to win the first prize in the [[Nicolay Rubinstein International Youth competition]] in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]].<ref name=\"incognito\"/>\n\nHe is one of the five members of the Syrian [[World music|world fusion]] band ''[[Hewar]]'', which formed in Damascus in 2003. This band, whose name means \"''dialogue''\" in [[Arabic language|Arabic]], and which also features Syrian soprano singer [[Dima Orsho]], is made up of musicians from Syria.<ref name=\"hewar\">[http://www.kinanazmeh.com/hewarmusic.htm Hewar] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622082912/http://www.kinanazmeh.com/hewarmusic.htm |date=2011-06-22 }}, on Azmeh's personal website</ref><ref name=\"npr\">[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101547802 Kinan Azmeh: A Syrian Frequent Flier With Clarinet in Hand.]  NPR, 7 March 2009.</ref>  On his website, Azmeh describes ''Hewar'' as \"an attempt to transcend the barriers of cultural disparities and misconceptions, and establish a civilized communication which builds on what brings humans closer together rather than separates them.\"<ref name=\"hewar\"/>  He claims that ''Hewar''<nowiki/>'s music draws from a variety of influences, from both the [[Arabic music|Arab world]] and the [[Western culture|West]].<ref name=\"hewar\"/>  In addition, Azmeh plays with the New York City-based City Band and with the band Neolexica.<ref name=\"sequenza\">[http://www.sequenza21.com/2010/08/be-here-now-kinan-azmeh-and-dinuk-wijeratne-down-san-francisco-way/ Be Here Now - Kinan Azmeh and Dinuk Wijeratne Down San Francisco Way.]  Sequenza, 16 August 2010.</ref>  As a student at Juillard, Azmeh co-founded Neolexica with pianist [[Dinuk Wijeratne]].<ref name=\"sequenza\"/>\n\nIn 2009, Azmeh played at the ''Arabesque Festival'' at the [[Kennedy Center]] in [[Washington D.C.]]<ref name=\"npr\"/> He has also played with the [[Syrian National Symphony Orchestra]], debuting a clarinet concerto written especially for him by Syrian composer [[Zaid Jabri]] at the opening of the [[Damascus Opera House]].<ref name=\"sequenza\"/> In addition, he has performed and recorded with [[Daniel Barenboim]]'s [[West-Eastern Divan Orchestra]],<ref name=\"sequenza\" /> as well as with [[Yo-Yo Ma]]'s [[The Silk Road Ensemble|Silk Road Ensemble]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-music-of-strangers-yo-yo-ma-and-the-silk-road-ensemble-review-grace-notes-from-all-over-1465499138|title=\u2018The Music of Strangers: Yo-Yo Ma and the Silk Road Ensemble\u2019 Review: Grace Notes From All Over|last=Morgenstern|first=Joe|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> He is also a permanent guest musician and workshop mentor of the [[Morgenland Festival Osnabr\u00fcck|Morgenland Festival]] in Osnabr\u00fcck, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.qantara.de/content/morgenland-festival-osnabruck-2016-from-the-balkans-to-the-levant|title=Morgenland Festival Osnabruck 2016: From the Balkans to the Levant - Qantara.de|website=Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he published a double CD called \"''Uneven Sky''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dreyer-gaido.de/index.php/de/katalog/10-katalog-cd/114-kinan-azmeh-uneven-sky|title=Kinan Azmeh - Uneven Sky|website=www.dreyer-gaido.de|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>, with Yo-Yo Ma as guest artist on cello and the [[Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin]], presenting works by Syrian contemporary composers as well as his own.\n\nAzmeh is currently based in [[New York City]], where he received his [[Ph.D.]] in 2013 at the [[City University of New York]] with [[Charles Neidich]].<ref name=\"azmehbio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.kinanazmeh.com/bio.htm |title=Biography of Kinan Azmeh |access-date=2012-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126180023/http://www.kinanazmeh.com/bio.htm |archive-date=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He regularly traveled to Damascus, where he played in a Syrian chamber group and has given numerous concerts and workshops.<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"sequenza\" /> These trips have  ended, however, since the beginning of the [[Syrian Civil War]] in 2011. In March 2017, Azmeh made international news, because he was unable to return to New York City for some time, following the issuance of [[Executive Order 13769]] by U.S. President Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kinan-azmeh-syrian-clarinetist-stranded-in-beirut-thanks-to-trump-ban-117856/ |title=Kinan Azmeh: Syrian Clarinetist Stranded in Beirut Thanks to Trump Ban |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=February 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n\n=== with Yo-Yo Ma and Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin ===\n\n*''Uneven Sky'' (2019), Opus Klassik Award in Germany\n\n=== with [[Eric Vloeimans]] and [[Jeroen van Vliet]]===\n*''Levant'' (2018). Live recording Rotterdam\n\n===with Hewar===\n*''[[Hewar (album)|Hewar]]'' (2005)\n*''[[9 Days of Solitude: The Damascus Session]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Letters to a homeland]]'' (2012)\n\n===with the Azmeh-Wijeratne Duo===\n*''[[Complex Stories, Simple Sounds]]'' (2009)\n\n===with the Kinan Azmeh Quartet===\n*''[[Elastic City]]'' (2012)\n\n===OST===\n*''[[Rigodon]]'' (2007)\n\n===With Kulna Sawa===\n*''Kulna Sawa'' (2001)\n*''Musaique'' (2004)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kinanazmeh.com/ Kinan Azmeh's official webpage]\n*[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_ID=10&article_ID=8022&categ_id=4 Daily Star Article]\n*[http://www.juilliard.edu/update/journal/j_articles277.html Gilgamesh performance at Juilliard School]\n*[https://www.npr.org/2013/01/29/169074246/daniel-barenboim-and-members-of-the-west-eastern-divan-orchestra?t=1588176065638 Kinan Azmeh: ''Prayer \u2013 A Tribute to Edward Said'']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCIqcvoriI2iMMCWO_ZQg_Wg Kinan Azmeh at Morgenland Festival Osnabr\u00fcck]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azmeh, Kinan}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Syrian clarinetists]]\n[[Category:People from Damascus]]\n[[Category:21st-century clarinetists]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Kinan Azmeh\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1976|6|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]\n| origin           = Syria\n| instrument       = [[Clarinet]]\n| genre            = [[Jazz fusion]], [[contemporary]]\n| occupation       = musician, composer\n}}\n\n'''Kinan Azmeh''' ({{lang-ar|\u0643\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0638\u0645\u0629|Kin\u0101n Azme}}, born June 10, 1976 in [[Damascus]]), is a [[Syrian]] [[clarinet]] player and composer of [[Contemporary Music|contemporary music]]. Performing with orchestras such as the [[New York Philharmonic]], the [[Seattle Symphony]], the [[Bavarian Radio Symphony Orchestra]], the [[West\u2013Eastern Divan Orchestra|West-Eastern Divan Orchestra]], or the Syrian Symphony Orchestra, he has played both as a [[Solo (music)|soloist]] of classical works as well as of contemporary compositions.\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Damascus]], [[Syria]] in 1976,<ref name=\"incognito\">[http://www.incognito.com.lb/store/node/235 Incognito] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503072702/http://www.incognito.com.lb/store/node/235 |date=2010-05-03 }} page on Azmeh</ref> Azmeh began to play the clarinet at age six. Originally taking lessons on the [[violin]], he switched to an even-handed instrument that left-handed players did not play too differently from right-handed players.<ref name=\"FW\">[http://www.fw-magazine.com/content/kinan-azmeh-i-am-living-example-whatthis-country-has-offer Interview with Azmeh]</ref>  Azmeh studied at the Arab conservatory of music in Damascus. At the [[University of Damascus]], he double-majored in [[electrical engineering]] and music.<ref name=\"epochtimes\">[http://www.theepochtimes.com/news/8-6-8/71470.html Epoch Times] article</ref>  Azmeh received his master's degree and graduate diploma in music from the [[Juilliard School]] in [[New York City]]. In 1997, Azmeh was the first Arab musician to win the first prize in the [[Nicolay Rubinstein International Youth competition]] in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]].<ref name=\"incognito\"/>\n\nHe is one of the five members of the Syrian [[World music|world fusion]] band ''[[Hewar]]'', which formed in Damascus in 2003. This band, whose name means \"''dialogue''\" in [[Arabic language|Arabic]], and which also features Syrian soprano singer [[Dima Orsho]], is made up of musicians from Syria.<ref name=\"hewar\">[http://www.kinanazmeh.com/hewarmusic.htm Hewar] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622082912/http://www.kinanazmeh.com/hewarmusic.htm |date=2011-06-22 }}, on Azmeh's personal website</ref><ref name=\"npr\">[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101547802 Kinan Azmeh: A Syrian Frequent Flier With Clarinet in Hand.]  NPR, 7 March 2009.</ref>  On his website, Azmeh describes ''Hewar'' as \"an attempt to transcend the barriers of cultural disparities and misconceptions, and establish a civilized communication which builds on what brings humans closer together rather than separates them.\"<ref name=\"hewar\"/>  He claims that ''Hewar''<nowiki/>'s music draws from a variety of influences, from both the [[Arabic music|Arab world]] and the [[Western culture|West]].<ref name=\"hewar\"/>  In addition, Azmeh plays with the New York City-based City Band and with the band Neolexica.<ref name=\"sequenza\">[http://www.sequenza21.com/2010/08/be-here-now-kinan-azmeh-and-dinuk-wijeratne-down-san-francisco-way/ Be Here Now - Kinan Azmeh and Dinuk Wijeratne Down San Francisco Way.]  Sequenza, 16 August 2010.</ref>  As a student at Juillard, Azmeh co-founded Neolexica with pianist [[Dinuk Wijeratne]].<ref name=\"sequenza\"/>\n\nIn 2009, Azmeh played at the ''Arabesque Festival'' at the [[Kennedy Center]] in [[Washington D.C.]]<ref name=\"npr\"/> He has also played with the [[Syrian National Symphony Orchestra]], debuting a clarinet concerto written especially for him by Syrian composer [[Zaid Jabri]] at the opening of the [[Damascus Opera House]].<ref name=\"sequenza\"/> In addition, he has performed and recorded with [[Daniel Barenboim]]'s [[West-Eastern Divan Orchestra]],<ref name=\"sequenza\" /> as well as with [[Yo-Yo Ma]]'s [[The Silk Road Ensemble|Silk Road Ensemble]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-music-of-strangers-yo-yo-ma-and-the-silk-road-ensemble-review-grace-notes-from-all-over-1465499138|title=\u2018The Music of Strangers: Yo-Yo Ma and the Silk Road Ensemble\u2019 Review: Grace Notes From All Over|last=Morgenstern|first=Joe|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> He is also a permanent guest musician and workshop mentor of the [[Morgenland Festival Osnabr\u00fcck|Morgenland Festival]] in Osnabr\u00fcck, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.qantara.de/content/morgenland-festival-osnabruck-2016-from-the-balkans-to-the-levant|title=Morgenland Festival Osnabruck 2016: From the Balkans to the Levant - Qantara.de|website=Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he published a double CD called \"''Uneven Sky''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dreyer-gaido.de/index.php/de/katalog/10-katalog-cd/114-kinan-azmeh-uneven-sky|title=Kinan Azmeh - Uneven Sky|website=www.dreyer-gaido.de|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>, with Yo-Yo Ma as guest artist on cello and the [[Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin]], presenting works by Syrian contemporary composers as well as his own.\n\nAzmeh is currently based in [[New York City]], where he received his [[Ph.D.]] in 2013 at the [[City University of New York]] with [[Charles Neidich]].<ref name=\"azmehbio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.kinanazmeh.com/bio.htm |title=Biography of Kinan Azmeh |access-date=2012-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126180023/http://www.kinanazmeh.com/bio.htm |archive-date=2009-11-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He regularly traveled to Damascus, where he played in a Syrian chamber group and has given numerous concerts and workshops.<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"sequenza\" /> These trips have  ended, however, since the beginning of the [[Syrian Civil War]] in 2011. In March 2017, Azmeh made international news, because he was unable to return to New York City for some time, following the issuance of [[Executive Order 13769]] by U.S. President Donald Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/kinan-azmeh-syrian-clarinetist-stranded-in-beirut-thanks-to-trump-ban-117856/ |title=Kinan Azmeh: Syrian Clarinetist Stranded in Beirut Thanks to Trump Ban |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=February 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n\n=== with Yo-Yo Ma and Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin ===\n\n*''Uneven Sky'' (2019), Opus Klassik Award in Germany\n\n=== with [[Eric Vloeimans]] and [[Jeroen van Vliet]]===\n*''Levant'' (2018). Live recording Rotterdam\n\n===with Hewar===\n*''[[Hewar (album)|Hewar]]'' (2005)\n*''[[9 Days of Solitude: The Damascus Session]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Letters to a homeland]]'' (2012)\n\n===with the Azmeh-Wijeratne Duo===\n*''[[Complex Stories, Simple Sounds]]'' (2009)\n\n===with the Kinan Azmeh Quartet===\n*''[[Elastic City]]'' (2012)\n\n===OST===\n*''[[Rigodon]]'' (2007)\n\n===With Kulna Sawa===\n*''Kulna Sawa'' (2001)\n*''Musaique'' (2004)\n\n*[https://www.discogs.com/artist/1367570-Kinan-Azmeh Kinan Azmeh on discogs]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kinanazmeh.com/ Kinan Azmeh's official webpage]\n*[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_ID=10&article_ID=8022&categ_id=4 Daily Star Article]\n*