, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass\n|-\n| 11 || A&R Studios || 19 September 1974 || Rehearsal and Takes 1\u20133, Remake || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass\n|-\n| 12 || A&R Studios || 19 September 1974 || 4 (remake) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass\n|-\n| 13{{efn|Previously released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]''}} || A&R Studios || 19 September 1974 || 4 (remake) \u2013 with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass\n|-\n| 14{{efn|Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''}} || Sound 80 || 27 December 1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; Billy Peterson: bass; Bill Berg: drums \n|-\n| 15{{efn|Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/bob-dylans-music-inspired-girl-north-country-announced-102635/ |title=Bob Dylan's The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country announced |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=19 December 2017 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407190304/https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/bob-dylans-music-inspired-girl-north-country-announced-102635/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} || ''The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legacyrecordings.co.uk/news/music-inspired-girl-north-country-now |title=The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country \u2013 Out Now |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=18 January 2018 |website=legacyrecordings.co.uk |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407190337/https://www.legacyrecordings.co.uk/news/music-inspired-girl-north-country-now |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> || 2018 || [[Sound 80]] || 27 December 1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums \n|}\n\n==Covers==\n[[Mary Lee's Corvette]] covered the entire ''Blood on The Tracks'' album in 2002, including \"Idiot Wind\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/mary-lees-corvette-blood-on-the-tracks-28113/ |title=Mary Lee's Corvette \u2013 Blood on the Tracks |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 February 2003 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> A cover of \"Idiot Wind\" was included on the [[Coal Porters]] album ''How Dark This Earth Will Shine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |title=Bob Dylan \u2013 Uncut January 2005 CDs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2004 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407154525/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind Lyrics to \"Idiot Wind\"] at bobdylan.com\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Dylan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|the Swedish artist|Amanda Bergman}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Idiot Wind\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blood on the Tracks]]\n| released = January 1975\n| recorded = 27 December 1974\n| studio   = [[Sound 80]],<br />[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\n| venue    = \n| genre    = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length   = 7:48\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer = Bob Dylan\n| tracks   = {{Blood on the Tracks tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Idiot Wind'''\" is a song by [[Bob Dylan]], which appeared on his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.  He began writing it in the summer of 1974, after his [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]]. Dylan recorded the song in September&nbsp;1974 and re-recorded it in December&nbsp;1974 along with some other from ''Blood on the Tracks''. Between the recordings, he often reworked the lyrics. A live version of the song was released on Dylan's 1976 album ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'', and all of the studio outtakes from the September sessions were released on the deluxe edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' in 2018. Some reviewers have speculated that the song is a reflection on Dylan's personal life, and in particular on his deteriorating relationship with his wife [[Sara Dylan]], whilst Dylan has denied that it is autobiographical.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nThe song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year and a separation from [[Sara Dylan]], who he had married in 1965. Dylan had moved to a farm in Minnesota with his brother, David Zimmerman, and there started to write the songs that were recorded for his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.<ref name=\"UNCUT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656/ |title=Shelter From The Storm \u2013 the inside story of Bob Dylan's Blood on the Tracks |last=Hasted |first=Nick |date=15 November 2013 | orig-year=2005 | work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011356/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 1974, Dylan had taken art classes at [[Carnegie Hall]] and was influenced by his tutor [[Norman Raeben]].<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Rogovoy2009\">{{cite book|author=Seth Rogovoy|title=Bob Dylan: Prophet, Mystic, Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdbgeObYgIkC&pg=PA160|date=24 November 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-5983-2}}</ref>{{rp|160}} and, in particular, Raeben's view of [[time]].<ref name=\"GillOdegard2004\">{{cite book|author1=Andy Gill|author2=Kevin Odegard|title=A Simple Twist of Fate: Bob Dylan and the Making of Blood on the Tracks|url=https://archive.org/details/simpletwistoffat00gill|url-access=registration|date=January 2004|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-81231-6|page=148}}</ref> Dylan was later to say that \"Idiot Wind\" was \"a song I wanted to make as a painting\".<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\">{{cite book|author=Bill Flanagan|title=Written in My Soul: Conversations with Rock's Great Songwriters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|date=1 April 2010|publisher=RosettaBooks|isbn=978-0-7953-1081-2|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506011534/https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Idiot Wind\" was a derogatory phrase employed by Raeben and this may have inspired Dylan's use of it, although the term also appears in the poem ''June&nbsp;1940'' by [[Weldon Kees]] and that may have been the reference point.<ref name=\"Wilentz2011\">{{cite book|author=Sean Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sb5UygkZlH0C&pg=PA140|date=15 February 2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4070-7411-5|}}{{rp|140-141}}</ref>\n\nDylan first recorded \"Idiot Wind\" in New York City on 16&nbsp;September 1974 during the initial ''Blood on the Tracks'' sessions at [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]]. That December, working from a suggestion from his brother that the album should have a more commercial sound, Dylan re-recorded half the songs on ''Blood on the Tracks'', including \"Idiot Wind\", in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /><ref name=\"OHAGAN\">{{cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Sean |title=The raw, painful birth of Blood on the Tracks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417055617/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks Review |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |work=BBC |year=2007 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919065715/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |archive-date=19 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe recordings were engineered by [[Phil Ramone]] in New York and by Paul Martinson in Minneapolis.In New York, the songs were recorded in the [[Key (music)|key]] of E, with Dylan's guitar was tuned to [[Open D tuning|open D]] with a [[capo]] on the second [[fret]], while the Minneapolis recordings are in [[standard tuning]].<ref name=\"Wise2017\">{{cite book|author=Wise Publications|title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEejDgAAQBAJ|date=8 April 2017|publisher=Wise Publications|isbn=978-1-78323-916-0}}</ref>\n\nThe re-recorded versions were radical departures from the original recordings, and each new recording included changes to the lyrics from the earlier versions.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Creswell2007\">{{cite book|author=Toby Creswell|title=1001 Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bhYnNaM0zEUC&pg=PA24|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing|isbn=1-74273-148-1|pages=24\u201325}}</ref><ref name=\"Dalton2012\">{{cite book|author=David Dalton|title=Who Is That Man? In Search of the Real Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SDcDAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT346|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-779-2|pages=346\u2013347}}</ref> The September&nbsp;1974 recording of \"Idiot Wind\" featured only acoustic guitar and bass accompaniment, with organ later [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]]<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /> whereas the re-recording made on 27&nbsp;December 1974 and issued on ''Blood on the Tracks'', featured a full band. This group of local musicians had been hurriedly put together, and Dylan had not previously met them.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"AMSO\" /> [[Clinton Heylin]] recounts that Dylan frequently reworked the song from September to December.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\">{{cite book|first=Clinton|last=Heylin|title=Still on the Road: The Songs of Bob Dylan Vol. 2 1974-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaSeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84901-494-6|pages=55\u201356}}</ref> In a 1991 interview with [[Paul Zollo]], Dylan said that there could be many more verses for the song and that it could be constantly reworked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn't stop. It wouldn't stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It's something that could be a work continually in progress.\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407113100/https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Zollo contrasts the ''Blood on the Tracks'' version with the one from ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' which was Take 4, with added organ overdubs, recorded on 19&nbsp;September 1974 in New York, and opines that the gentler delivery of the song in the September version \"makes the inherent disquiet of the song even more disturbing\".<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |title=Read the complete tracklisting for Bob Dylan's More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=20 September 2018 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407115523/https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ZOLLO2\" />\n\nIndividual outtakes from the New York sessions were released in 1991<ref name=\"Varesi2002\">{{cite book|author=Anthony Varesi|title=The Bob Dylan Albums: A Critical Study|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5M4EkqYcyJUC&pg=PA194|year=2002|publisher=Guernica Editions|isbn=978-1-55071-139-4|page=194}}</ref> on ''The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133'' and in 2018 on the single-CD and 2-LP versions of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks|The Bootleg Series Vol. 14]]'', while the complete New York sessions were released on the deluxe edition of the latter album. The deluxe version of  ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'' also included a remix of the December 1974 master issued on ''Blood on the Tracks''.<ref name=\"MBMTREL\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretations ==\nBarbara O'Dair links the song to two of Dylan's other compositions, \"[[Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands]]\" (1966) and \"[[Sara (Bob Dylan song)|Sara]]\" (1976), as a set of songs written across ten years \"addressing a woman that bears a resemblance to his now ex-wife Sara Lowndes\".{{efn|Sara Dylan was known as Sara Lownds before marrying Bob Dylan.}} O'Dair criticises the song for [[victim blaming]].<ref name=\"ODAIR2009\">{{cite book |last=O'Dair |first=Barbara |editor-last1=Dettmar |editor-first1=Kevin |title=The Cambridge Companion to Bob Dylan |page= 83 |chapter=Bob Dylan and gender politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73eAjOofhCAC|date=19 February 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82843-7}}</ref> David Goldblatt and Edward Necarsulmer say that in the song, \"Dylan explores the bitterness of resentment and revenge against a lover and one's own self who botched their love\".<ref name=\"PVI2011\">{{cite book |last1=Goldblatt |first1=David |last2=Necarsulmer IV |first2=Edward |editor-last1=Porter |editor-first1=Carl J. |editor-last2=Vernezze |editor-first2=Peter |editor-last3=Irwin |editor-first3=William |title=Bob Dylan and Philosophy: It's Alright Ma (I'm Only Thinking) |publisher=Open Court |date=2011 |page=163 |chapter=Language on the Lam(b): Tarantula in Dylan and Nietzsche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JaOqtb977hQC |isbn=978-0-8126-9760-5 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> Dylan has denied that the song is personal, stating in 1985 that:<ref name=\"WILLMAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |title=Dylan's blood-best album: 40 facts about the 40-year-old Blood On The Tracks |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=21 January 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405155031/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|I thought I might have gone a little bit too far with \"Idiot Wind\" ... I didn't really think I was giving away too much; I thought that it seemed so personal that people would think it was about so-and-so who was close to me. It wasn't ... I didn't feel that one was too personal, but I felt it seemed too personal. Which might be the same thing, I don't know.}}\n\nTimothy Hampton takes the song as political, and a commentary on the [[Vietnam War]],<ref name=\"Hampton2019\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Hampton|title=Bob Dylan's Poetics: How the Songs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51WRDwAAQBAJ|date=26 March 2019|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|isbn=978-1-942130-15-4}}</ref> whereas David Dalton feels that Dylan draws parallels between his personal situation and the national one, and \"turns his own fate into an allegory of a soured American dream\".<ref name=\"Dalton2012\" />\n\nDylan and Lowndes' relationship deteriorated in 1976, and David Kinney relates how Dylan played \"Idiot Wind\" in a show at Fort Collins whilst Lowndes was in the audience, noting in the following sentence that the pair were divorced the following year.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" />{{rp|95}}\n\nThis live version from 23&nbsp;May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''&thinsp;<ref name=\"BowdenDylan2001\">{{cite book|author1=Betsy Bowden|author2=Bob Dylan|title=Performed Literature: Words and Music by Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CN0HAQAAMAAJ|date=1 January 2001|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0-7618-1947-9}}</ref><ref name\"ALHR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref> and was also included on the Dylan album ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' that was released in Japan and Australia.<ref name=\"BJ762\" /><ref name=\"Bell2013\">{{cite book|author=Ian Bell|title=Time Out of Mind: The Lives of Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbx8AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT614|date=12 September 2013|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|isbn=978-1-78057-835-4|page=614}}</ref> It contained lyrical changes from the album version. Mick Farren's review of the album says that \"It requires a considerable sleight of hand to get across the remorseless emotional attack of, say, \"Idiot Wind\" without losing the party atmosphere. I haven't quite worked out how he managed it.\"<ref name=\"FARREN\">{{cite magazine |last=Farren |first=Mick |date=25 September 1976 |title=Bob Dylan: Hard Rain |url=http://www.rocksbackpages.com.wikipedialibrary.idm.oclc.org/Library/Article/bob-dylan-hard-rain- |magazine=New Musical Express|access-date=29 April 2020 ||url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1985 interview with Bill Flanagan, Dylan said that although many people thought that \"Idiot Wind\" and the album ''Blood on the Tracks'' related to his life, \"It didn't pertain to me. It was just a concept of putting in images that defy time&nbsp;&ndash; yesterday, today and tomorrow. I wanted to make them all connect in some kind of a strange way.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\" /> In his 2004 memoir ''[[Chronicles: Volume One]]'', Dylan claimed that ''Blood on the Tracks'' was \"an entire album based on [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]] short stories. Critics thought it was autobiographical&nbsp;\u2013 that was fine.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album ''Blood on the Tracks'' received mixed reviews on release.<ref name=\"Williamson2004\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Williamson|title=The Rough Guide to Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R2c8AQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-139-5}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' carried two reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/10-classic-albums-rolling-stone-originally-panned-101316/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-1975-101880/ |title=10 Classic Albums Rolling Stone Originally Panned  |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=25 July 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jonathan Cott described the album as \"magnificent and memorable\" and \"Idiot Wind\", which he saw as equally as accomplished as the other songs, as \"explosive and bitter\", Cott observed that it was the first time that Dylan had included himself in a condemnation in one of his songs, with the line \"We're idiots, babe/It's a wonder we can even feed ourselves\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-55031/  |title=Bob Dylan: Blood on the Tracks  |last=Cott |first=Jonathan |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, in the other ''Rolling Stone'' review, [[Jon Landau]] disparaged \"the childishness (without any redeeming childlike wonder) of so much of 'Idiot Wind{{'\"}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |title=Blood on the Tracks |last=Landau |first=Jon |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230122112/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Music critic [[Lester Bangs]] originally regarded the song as \"ridiculously spiteful\" and was unimpressed, although he soon found himself listening to the album frequently.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|first=David |last=Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0}}{{rp|95}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2003 book ''[[Dylan's Visions of Sin]]'', literary scholar [[Christopher Ricks]] discusses a particular lyrical couplet from the song, namely: \"Blowing like a circle around my skull/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the Capitol\". Ricks praises this as<ref name=\"Ricks2011\">{{cite book|first=Christopher|last=Ricks|authorlink=Christopher Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlDWua9p8lEC|date=5 May 2011|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-0-85786-202-0}}</ref> {{quote|fierce ... And it's a true rhyme because of the metaphorical relation, because of what a head of state is, and the body politic, and because of the relation of the Capitol to the skull (another of those white domes), with which it disconcertingly rhymes. An imperfect rhyme, perfectly judged.}} The same rhyme had impressed [[Allen Ginsberg]], who wrote to Dylan comparing it to an image from ''[[The Bridge (long poem)|The Bridge]]'' by [[Hart Crane]]. Dylan was apparently gratified to receive Ginsberg's letter, and it was a contributing factor in leading to Ginsberg being invited onto the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]] tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/on-the-road-with-bob-dylan-joan-baez-and-the-rolling-thunder-revue-183508/ |title=On the Road With Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the Rolling Thunder Revue  |last=Hentoff |first=Nat |date=15 January 1976 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In his 1976 review in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Paul Cowan also referred to these lyrics, saying that they evoked both [[Woody Guthrie]] in the language used and [[T.&nbsp;S. Elliot]] in the delivery of the vocal. Like Cott, Cowan noted the ultimately self-accusatory nature of the lyrics, which he felt provided a surprising conclusion to the song.<ref name=\"COWAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |title=Riffs: Bob Dylan's Pain \u2014 Flip Side of Cruelty |last=Cowan |first=Paul |date=13 February 2020 |orig-year=1975 |work=The Village Voice |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316142900/https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lyrics referencing the Capitol replaced the earlier \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your jaw/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the Mardi Gras\" used in New York.<ref name=\"Burger2018\">{{cite book|author=Jeff Burger|title=Dylan on Dylan: Interviews and Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT257|date=1 May 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-0-912777-44-3|page=257}}</ref> Zollo also felt that this pair of lines was the highlight of the song.<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\">{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407120144/https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[1001 Songs]]'', [[Toby Creswell]] says that the track is an \"epic of elegantly phrased bile\" and is \"not ... based on logical exposition\".<ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /> The song was 16th on '' [[American Songwriter]]'' magazine's 2009 ranking of ''The 30 Greatest Dylan Songs'',<ref name=\"AMSO\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-16-idiot-wind/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #16, \"Idiot Wind\"|author=Schlansky, Evan|date=20 April 2009|publisher=americansongwriter.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and placed fourth in Jim Beviglia's 2013 book ''Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs''.<ref name=\"Beviglia2013\">{{cite book|author=Jim Beviglia|title=Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRMeAAAAQBAJ|date=11 July 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8824-1}}</ref> In a 2020 article for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Alexis Petridis]] ranked it the third-greatest of Dylan's songs, praising it as \"extraordinary, harrowing listening\" and quoting the lyric \"I haven't known peace and quiet for so long I can't remember what it's like\", commenting \"its author isn't just hurling bitter accusations, he's writhing in agony\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Petridis |first=Alexis |title=Bob Dylan's 50 greatest songs \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/09/bob-dylans-50-greatest-songs-ranked |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=9 April 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409235447/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/09/bob-dylans-50-greatest-songs-ranked |archive-date=9 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'', Sean O'Hagan remarked of the song \"By turns paranoid, derisory and vengeful, it is a dark masterpiece of venomous intent, a great part of its raw power resting in the very discomfort the listener feels as it gathers momentum and the tone becomes ever more bitter.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" /> When Dylan won the [[Nobel prize for literature]] in 2016, ''The Guardian'' cited \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your teeth/ You're an idiot, babe/ It's a wonder that you still know how to breathe\" from \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his greatest lyrics.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Are these the lyrics that won Bob Dylan a Nobel prize? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521040933/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |archive-date=21 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nDylan has performed the song live only 55 times. The first was on 18&nbsp;April 1976 at Civic Centre, Lakeland, Florida. He retired the song from his setlist the following month and did not perform it again until April&nbsp;1992, retiring it again in August of that year.<ref name=\"BDIW\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists that contain Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1992, [[Clinton Heylin]], a prolific author of material about Dylan, flew from England to California to attend Dylan's shows when he heard that \"Idiot Wind\" was being played live again.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" />{{rp|129}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nArtist Mohammad Omer Khalil produced a series of etchings, inspired by Dylan's music, that were displayed at the [[National Museum of African Art]] in 1994, including one entitled ''Idiot Wind''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africa.si.edu/collections/view/objects/asitem/People@120/2?t:state:flow=847c62c4-c3b4-469a-baaf-52952b9c28ed |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=africa.si.edu |publisher=National Museum of African Art |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of the lyrics of \"Idiot Wind\" are mentioned in the 1995 song \"[[Only Wanna Be with You]]\" by American band [[Hootie & the Blowfish]]. The use of Dylan's lyrics reportedly led to an out-of-court settlement, with Dylan receiving money from Hootie & the Blowfish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|title=Darius Rucker on 'Wagon Wheel' and the Future of Hootie|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=19 July 2013|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023200015/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSwedish musician [[Amanda Bergman]] used to perform under the stage name ''Idiot Wind'', after the song.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|title = Hajen som blev Jaw Lesson blir nu Idiot Wind |trans-title=The shark that became Jaw Lesson is now Idiot Wind|date = 13 September 2010|website = svt.se|publisher = [[Sveriges Television]]|last = Beckman|first = Eva|language = Swedish|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426205311/http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|archivedate = 26 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/bob-dylan/bob-dylan-you-been-on-my-mind-9-best-covers/ |title=The 9 Best Covers of Bob Dylan's 1964 Classic \"Mama You Been on My Mind\" |last=Burgos |first=Jenzia |date=8 June 2018 |website=pastemagazine.com |publisher=Paste Media Group |access-date=29 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411101835/https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/bob-dylan/bob-dylan-you-been-on-my-mind-9-best-covers/ |archive-date=11 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a question on the \"Ask Lou\" section of his website in 2007, singer-songwriter [[Lou Reed]] picked \"Idiot Wind\" as the song he wished he had written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |work=loureed.com |title=Ask Lou |date=December 2007 |access-date=12 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415130637/http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |archive-date=15 April 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Novelist [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] included \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his eight records for BBC Radio 4's ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |title=Peter Carey |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 2008 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702063046/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |archive-date=2 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | people = Young, Christie; Carey, Peter | date =20 June 2008 | work=Desert Island Discs | title =Peter Carey | medium =Podcast | language =en | url =https://open.live.bbc.co.uk/mediaselector/6/redir/version/2.0/mediaset/audio-nondrm-download/proto/https/vpid/p02pp00s.mp3\n | access-date =27 April 2020 | format =mp3 | time = 24:23<!--elapsed time at which material is cited--><!--\"Thunder on the Mountain\" at 16:50--> | publisher =BBC Radio 5 | id = | isbn = | oclc = | quote = This mad, raging song was a source of great comfort to me.}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in [[Conor McPherson]]'s play ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]''.<ref name=\"McPherson2017\">{{cite book|author=Conor McPherson|title=Girl from the North Country|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2FhDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT9|date=20 November 2017|publisher=Theatre Communications Group|isbn=978-1-55936-882-7|page=9}}</ref> In the original 2017 London production at [[The Old Vic]] and the subsequent transfer to the [[West End theatre|West End]] it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], playing the role of Marianne Laine, as part of a medley with \"[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]\" and \"[[All Along the Watchtower]]\" sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"RWG\">{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Richard |title=Girl from the North Country lets us hear Bob Dylan's mysteries anew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 January 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150058/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bano |first=Tim |title=Girl from the North Country star Sheila Atim: 'You don't want to be a freedom fighter every time you enter a job' |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/girl-north-country-star-sheila-atim-time-is-love-les-blancs-game-of-thrones/ |work=The Stage |date=15 January 2019 |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707225258/https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/girl-north-country-star-sheila-atim-time-is-love-les-blancs-game-of-thrones/ |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Atim won the 2018 Laurence Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Musical for her role.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Olivier Awards 2018: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930235126/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |archive-date=30 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The cast recording, recorded at [[Abbey Road Studios]], includes the song in a medley performed by Atim and Kene, as per the original London production.<ref name=\"RWG\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oldvictheatre.com/news/2017/08/the-girl-from-the-north-country-cast-recording |title=The Girl from the North Country cast recording is here |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 August 2017 |website=oldvictheatre.com |publisher=The Old Vic |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nPeter Kaldheim's 2019 novel ''Idiot Wind: A Memoir'' was published by Canongate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|title=Idiot Wind by Peter Kaldheim \u2013 Canongate Books|website=canongate.co.uk|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715152051/https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |title=In Idiot Wind, a Lost Soul Finds His Way Home |last=Williams |first=John |date=28 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729233051/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |archive-date=29 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\nThe officially released versions of the song on Bob Dylan albums are below.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" /><ref name=\"MBMTREL\" /><ref name=\"BDIW\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904013229/https://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |archive-date=4 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BJ762\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |title=1976 soon to be divorced |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=[[Olof Bj\u00f6rner]] |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212094032/http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |archive-date=12 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |title=Still on the road: 1976 Rolling Thunder Revue II |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901094048/http://bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |archive-date=1 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bell2013\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  !! Album !! Release Year !! Recorded at !! Recording date !! [[Take]] !! Personnel !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'' || 1975 || [[Sound 80]] || 27 December 1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums ||\n|-\n| 2 || ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'' || 1976 || [[Sonny Lubick Field at Hughes Stadium|Hughes Stadium]] || 23 May 1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, [[Scarlet Rivera]]: violin; [[T Bone Burnett|T-bone J. Henry Burnett]]: guitar, piano; [[Steven Soles]]: guitar; [[Mick Ronson]]: guitar; [[Bob Neuwirth|Bobby Neuwirth]]: guitar, vocals; [[Roger McGuinn]]: guitar, vocals; [[David Mansfield]]: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; [[Rob Stoner]]: bass; [[Howard Wyeth|Howie Wyeth]]: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || \n|-\n| 3 || ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' || 1978 || Hughes Stadium || 23 May 1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, Scarlet Rivera: violin; T-bone J. Henry Burnett: guitar, piano; Steven Soles: guitar; Mick Ronson: guitar; Bobby Neuwirth: guitar, vocals; Roger McGuinn: guitar, vocals; David Mansfield: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; Rob Stoner: bass; Howie Wyeth: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || Previously