an; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; Billy Peterson: bass; Bill Berg: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''\n|-\n| 15 || ''The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legacyrecordings.co.uk/news/music-inspired-girl-north-country-now |title=The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country \u2013 Out Now |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=18 January 2018 |website=legacyrecordings.co.uk |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407190337/https://www.legacyrecordings.co.uk/news/music-inspired-girl-north-country-now |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> || 2018 || [[Sound 80]] || 27 December 1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/bob-dylans-music-inspired-girl-north-country-announced-102635/ |title=Bob Dylan's The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country announced |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=19 December 2017 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407190304/https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/bob-dylans-music-inspired-girl-north-country-announced-102635/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Covers==\n[[Mary Lee's Corvette]] covered the entire ''Blood on The Tracks'' album in 2002, including \"Idiot Wind\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/mary-lees-corvette-blood-on-the-tracks-28113/ |title=Mary Lee's Corvette \u2013 Blood on the Tracks |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 February 2003 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> A cover of \"Idiot Wind\" was included on the [[Coal Porters]] album ''How Dark This Earth Will Shine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |title=Bob Dylan \u2013 Uncut January 2005 CDs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2004 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407154525/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind Lyrics to \"Idiot Wind\"] at bobdylan.com\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Dylan]]\n", "name_user": "BennyOnTheLoose", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReleases:removed stray punctuation mark; moved notes to efns", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idiot_Wind"}
{"title_page": "Open the Door to Your Heart", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Open the Door to Your Heart\n| cover      = Open the Door to Your Heart .jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Darrell Banks]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Our Love (Is in the Pocket)\n| released   = 1966\n| format     = 7-inch single\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soul music|Soul]]\n| length     = 2:37\n| label      = [[Revilot Records|Revilot]]\n| writer     = [[Donnie Elbert]], Darrell Banks\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Open the Door to Your Heart'''\" is a song and [[single (music)|single]] by American [[soul music|soul]] singer, [[Darrell Banks]]. Written by Banks and [[Donnie Elbert]], it was first released in 1966.<ref name=am>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Darrell-Banks-Open-The-Door-To-Your-Heart/release/2380244| title=Open The Door to Your Heart | publisher=[[Discogs]] | accessdate= 15 December 2014}}</ref> It has been described as \"one of the finest non-[[Motown]] releases to emerge from [[Detroit]]\".<ref name=\"Hoffmann2005\">{{cite book|author=Frank Hoffmann|title=Rhythm and Blues, Rap, and Hip-hop|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wNfx07-AJwcC&pg=PA10|year=2005|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6980-4|pages=10\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Background and chart success==\nReleased in the US in 1966 on the [[Revilot Records|Revilot]] label, the song made number two on the [[R&B charts]] and number 27 on the [[Billboard charts]] in 1966 and was Banks' biggest hit. Based on chart positions throughout the year, it ranked 14th in a list of top R&B singles for 1966.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/300315/darrell-banks/chart | title=Darrell Banks | publisher=www.billboard.com | accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Inc.1966\">{{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_hSIEAAAAMBAJ|date=24 December 1966|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_hSIEAAAAMBAJ/page/n33 34]\u2013|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Although written by Banks' friend, Donnie Elbert, and called \"Baby, Walk Right In\" as a [[working title]], Banks completed the recording and changed its name, while Elbert was on tour.<ref name=\"Simmons2013\">{{cite book|author=Rick Simmons|title=Carolina Beach Music from the '60s to the '80s: The New Wave|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ojgVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA72|date=26 February 2013|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-1-61423-864-5|pages=72\u2013}}</ref> When released, writing credits were given to Banks on the record label. Having checking with [[Broadcast Music, Inc.]], a performing rights organization, Elbert discovered that a song clearance form submitted by Banks had him listed as the sole writer which would entitle him to 100% of [[Performance royalties|performance income]].<ref name=\"Simmons2011\">{{cite book|author=Rick Simmons|title=Carolina Beach Music: The Classic Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ArwpZYvQwJ8C&pg=PA22|date=22 November 2011|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-1-61423-180-6|pages=22\u2013}}</ref>\nElbert sought legal action and although initial releases of the [[Gramophone record|vinyl]] [[45rpm single]] list only Banks' name as songwriter, later released CDs credit both Banks and Elbert. Never content with the ruling, Elbert claimed that for a 50% share of writing credits Banks' contribution was to slightly speed up the [[tempo]]. Not considered to be a songwriter, \"Open the Door to Your Heart\" is the only song which Banks wrote but as Elbert claimed, he played no part in the writing.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/darrell-banks-mn0000565727/biography | title=Darrell Banks | publisher=AllMusic | accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> Motown\u2019s [[Mike Terry (saxophonist)|Mike Terry]] played the baritone saxophone on both songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/dec/01/mike-terry-obituary|title=Obituary: Mike Terry|first=Richard|last=Williams|date=December 1, 2008|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref> The [[B side]] was \"Our Love (Is in the Pocket)\" written by [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], [[Joanne Jackson (singer)|Joanne Jackson]] and [[Rose Marie McCoy]]. This was another favourite of the [[Northern soul]] scene when covered by [[J. J. Barnes]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Virgin Encyclopedia of R&B and Soul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ci7aAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Virgin|isbn=978-0-7535-0241-9}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966 the record was released in the UK on the [[London Records|London]] label only for the release to be pulled as it was discovered that the label did not own the rights to the song. Consequently, it was released in the UK on the [[Stateside Records|Stateside]] label and became very popular on the Northern soul music scene.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/jun/27/souls-holy-grail-why-the-rarest-record-in-the-world-is-causing-so-much-fuss | title=Soul's holy grail: why the rarest record in the world is causing so much fuss | work=The Guardian | date=27 June 2014 | accessdate=16 December 2014 | author=Stanley, Bob}}</ref> In December 2014, collectors were bidding in excess of \u00a311,000 for a copy of the London Records single, thought to be the only copy still in existence. It had previously been thought that all the original versions had been destroyed when rival label [[EMI Records|EMI]] won the rights to release the single in the UK.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30480779 | title=Northern Soul fans in a spin over sale of rare record | publisher=BBC News | date=15 December 2014 | accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> The copy eventually sold for \u00a314,543.<ref name=\"14kplus\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/open-the-door-to-your-heart-by-darrell-banks-holy-grail-northern-soul-single-sells-for-14543-9939078.html | title=Open The Door To Your Heart by Darrell Banks: 'Holy grail' Northern Soul single sells for \u00a314,543 | work=The Independent | date=22 December 2014 | accessdate=23 December 2014 | author=Apps, Peter}}</ref>\n\n==References== \n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:1966 singles]]\n[[Category:American soul songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Donnie Elbert]]\n[[Category:Northern soul songs]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in royalties controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Open the Door to Your Heart\n| cover      = Open the Door to Your Heart .jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Darrell Banks]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Our Love (Is in the Pocket)\n| released   = 1966\n| format     = 7-inch single\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soul Music|Soul]]\n| length     = 2:37\n| label      = [[Revilot Records|Revilot]]\n| writer     = [[Donnie Elbert]], Darrell Banks\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Open the Door to Your Heart'''\" is a song and [[single (music)|single]] by American [[soul music|soul]] singer, [[Darrell Banks]]. Written by Banks and [[Donnie Elbert]], it was first released in 1966.<ref name=am>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Darrell-Banks-Open-The-Door-To-Your-Heart/release/2380244| title=Open The Door to Your Heart | publisher=[[Discogs]] | accessdate= 15 December 2014}}</ref> It has been described as \"one of the finest non-[[Motown]] releases to emerge from [[Detroit]]\".<ref name=\"Hoffmann2005\">{{cite book|author=Frank Hoffmann|title=Rhythm and Blues, Rap, and Hip-hop|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wNfx07-AJwcC&pg=PA10|year=2005|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6980-4|pages=10\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Background and chart success==\nReleased in the US in 1966 on the [[Revilot Records|Revilot]] label, the song made number two on the [[R&B charts]] and number 27 on the [[Billboard charts]] in 1966 and was Banks' biggest hit. Based on chart positions throughout the year, it ranked 14th in a list of top R&B singles for 1966.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/300315/darrell-banks/chart | title=Darrell Banks | publisher=www.billboard.com | accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Inc.1966\">{{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_hSIEAAAAMBAJ|date=24 December 1966|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_hSIEAAAAMBAJ/page/n33 34]\u2013|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Although written by Banks' friend, Donnie Elbert, and called \"Baby, Walk Right In\" as a [[working title]], Banks completed the recording and changed its name, while Elbert was on tour.<ref name=\"Simmons2013\">{{cite book|author=Rick Simmons|title=Carolina Beach Music from the '60s to the '80s: The New Wave|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ojgVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA72|date=26 February 2013|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-1-61423-864-5|pages=72\u2013}}</ref> When released, writing credits were given to Banks on the record label. Having checking with [[Broadcast Music, Inc.]], a performing rights organization, Elbert discovered that a song clearance form submitted by Banks had him listed as the sole writer which would entitle him to 100% of [[Performance royalties|performance income]].<ref name=\"Simmons2011\">{{cite book|author=Rick Simmons|title=Carolina Beach Music: The Classic Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ArwpZYvQwJ8C&pg=PA22|date=22 November 2011|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-1-61423-180-6|pages=22\u2013}}</ref>\nElbert sought legal action and although initial releases of the [[Gramophone record|vinyl]] [[45rpm single]] list only Banks' name as songwriter, later released CDs credit both Banks and Elbert. Never content with the ruling, Elbert claimed that for a 50% share of writing credits Banks' contribution was to slightly speed up the [[tempo]]. Not considered to be a songwriter, \"Open the Door to Your Heart\" is the only song which Banks wrote but as Elbert claimed, he played no part in the writing.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/darrell-banks-mn0000565727/biography | title=Darrell Banks | publisher=AllMusic | accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> Motown\u2019s [[Mike Terry (saxophonist)|Mike Terry]] played the baritone saxophone on both songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/dec/01/mike-terry-obituary|title=Obituary: Mike Terry|first=Richard|last=Williams|date=December 1, 2008|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref> The [[B side]] was \"Our Love (Is in the Pocket)\" written by [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]], [[Joanne Jackson (singer)|Joanne Jackson]] and [[Rose Marie McCoy]]. This was another favourite of the [[Northern soul]] scene when covered by [[J. J. Barnes]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Virgin Encyclopedia of R&B and Soul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ci7aAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Virgin|isbn=978-0-7535-0241-9}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966 the record was released in the UK on the [[London Records|London]] label only for the release to be pulled as it was discovered that the label did not own the rights to the song. Consequently, it was released in the UK on the [[Stateside Records|Stateside]] label and became very popular on the Northern soul music scene.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/jun/27/souls-holy-grail-why-the-rarest-record-in-the-world-is-causing-so-much-fuss | title=Soul's holy grail: why the rarest record in the world is causing so much fuss | work=The Guardian | date=27 June 2014 | accessdate=16 December 2014 | author=Stanley, Bob}}</ref> In December 2014, collectors were bidding in excess of \u00a311,000 for a copy of the London Records single, thought to be the only copy still in existence. It had previously been thought that all the original versions had been destroyed when rival label [[EMI Records|EMI]] won the rights to release the single in the UK.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30480779 | title=Northern Soul fans in a spin over sale of rare record | publisher=BBC News | date=15 December 2014 | accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> The copy eventually sold for \u00a314,543.<ref name=\"14kplus\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/open-the-door-to-your-heart-by-darrell-banks-holy-grail-northern-soul-single-sells-for-14543-9939078.html | title=Open The Door To Your Heart by Darrell Banks: 'Holy grail' Northern Soul single sells for \u00a314,543 | work=The Independent | date=22 December 2014 | accessdate=23 December 2014 | author=Apps, Peter}}</ref>\n\n==References== \n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:1966 singles]]\n[[Category:American soul songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Donnie Elbert]]\n[[Category:Northern soul songs]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in royalties controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSoul music (disambiguation)(link changed toSoul music) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_the_Door_to_Your_Heart"}
{"title_page": "Tony Macaulay", "text_new": "{{about|the English writer and composer|the Northern Irish writer, management consultant and peace builder|Tony Macaulay (writer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image               = \n| name                = Tony Macaulay\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Anthony Gordon Instone\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1944|4|21}}\n| origin              = [[Fulham]], London, England\n| genre               = \n| occupation          = [[Record producer]]<br/>[[Composer]]<br/>[[Songwriter]]<br/>[[Author]]\n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = [http://www.tonymacaulay.com/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''Tony Macaulay''' (born '''Anthony Gordon Instone''', 21 April 1944)<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|last=Eder |first=Bruce |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/tony-macaulay-mn0000009429 |title=Tony Macaulay - Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date=1944-04-21 |accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> is an [[English people|English]] [[author]], [[composer]] for [[musical theatre]], and [[songwriter]]. He has won the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors]] Award twice as 'Songwriter of the Year' (1970 and 1977).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |title=Official Website |publisher=Tony Macaulay |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222112549/http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |archivedate=22 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He is a nine time [[Ivor Novello Awards]] winning songwriter. In 2007, he became the only British person to win the Edwin Forrest Award for outstanding contribution to the American theatre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |title=Official Website |publisher=Tony Macaulay |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222112549/http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |archivedate=22 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMacaulay's best-known songs include \"[[Baby Now That I've Found You]]\" and \"[[Build Me Up Buttercup]]\" with [[The Foundations]], \"[[(Last Night) I Didn't Get to Sleep at All]],\" as well as \"[[Love Grows (Where My Rosemary Goes)]]\" and \"[[Don't Give Up on Us (song)|Don't Give Up on Us]]\".\n\n==Career==\nMacaulay was born in [[Fulham]], London, England.<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nIn the early 1960s he worked as a [[song plugger]] for [[Howie Richmond|Essex Publishing]], then moved to [[Pye Records]] as a [[record producer]].<ref name=\"AMG\"/>  It was here that he had his first major success with [[The Foundations]], when they [[sound recording and reproduction|recorded]], \"[[Baby Now That I've Found You]]\", a [[song]] he had co-written with [[John Macleod (songwriter)|John Macleod]], and it topped the [[UK Singles Chart]] in November 1967.<ref name=\"AMG\"/><ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 209}}</ref>  \n\nFurther [[hit single|hits]] came with songs such as [[Marmalade (band)|Marmalade]]'s \"[[Baby Make It Soon]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/baby-make-it-soon-mt0003528787 |title=Baby Make It Soon - Marmalade : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and \"Falling Apart at the Seams\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/falling-apart-at-the-seams-mt0001127531 |title=Falling Apart at the Seams - Marmalade : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[The 5th Dimension]]'s \"[[(Last Night) I Didn't Get to Sleep at All]]\",<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwald |first=Matthew |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/last-night-i-didnt-get-to-sleep-at-all-mt0013274873 |title=(Last Night) I Didn't Get to Sleep at All - The 5th Dimension : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[David Soul]]'s \"[[Don't Give Up on Us (song)|Don't Give Up on Us]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/David-Soul-Dont-Give-Up-On-Us-Black-Bean-Soup/release/1339153 |title=David Soul - Don't Give Up On Us / Black Bean Soup (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> plus [[Donna Summer]]'s 1977 [[single (music)|single]] \"[[Can't We Just Sit Down (And Talk It Over)]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Donna-Summer-Cant-We-Just-Sit-Down-And-Talk-It-Over-I-Feel-Love/release/53270 |title=Donna Summer - Can't We Just Sit Down (And Talk It Over) / I Feel Love (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> each of which he wrote on his own. Many others came in collaboration with other songwriters, amongst them were [[Long John Baldry]]'s \"[[Let the Heartaches Begin]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/let-the-heartaches-begin-mt0000849004 |title=Let the Heartaches Begin - Long John Baldry : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[Paper Dolls (band)|Paper Dolls]]' \"[[Something Here in My Heart (Keeps A Tellin' Me No)]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/something-here-in-my-heart-keeps-a-tellin-me-no-mt0013029607 |title=Something Here in My Heart (Keeps A-Tellin' Me No) - Paper Dolls : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and [[Pickettywitch]]'s \"[[That Same Old Feeling]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/that-same-old-feeling-mt0026811380 |title=That Same Old Feeling - Pickettywitch : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> all co-written with John Macleod.  Another success for The Foundations was \"[[Build Me Up Buttercup]]\", written by Macaulay and [[Mike D'Abo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/build-me-up-buttercup-mt0011268256 |title=Build Me Up Buttercup - The Foundations : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]]'s \"[[Lights of Cincinnati]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Scott-Walker-Lights-Of-Cincinnati/release/1207970 |title=Scott Walker - Lights Of Cincinnati (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> [[The Hollies]]' \"[[Sorry Suzanne]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/sorry-suzanne-mt0000010583 |title=Sorry Suzanne - The Hollies : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> [[The New Seekers]]' \"[[You Won't Find Another Fool Like Me]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/you-wont-find-another-fool-like-me-mt0001007944 |title=You Won't Find Another Fool Like Me - The New Seekers : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\"AMG\"/> were penned with [[Geoff Stephens]]; whilst [[Edison Lighthouse]]'s \"[[Love Grows (Where My Rosemary Goes)]]\", was written with Sylvan Whittingham and [[Barry Mason]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/love-grows-where-my-rosemary-goes-mt0011983238 |title=Love Grows (Where My Rosemary Goes) - Edison Lighthouse : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>  In addition, he co-wrote [[Johnny Johnson and the Bandwagon]]'s \"Blame It On The Pony Express\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Johnny-Johnson-And-His-Bandwagon-Blame-It-On-The-Pony-Express/release/3449134 |title=Johnny Johnson And His Bandwagon* - (Blame It) On The Pony Express (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and [[Andy Williams]]' \"[[Home Lovin' Man]]\", with [[Roger Cook (songwriter)|Roger Cook]] and [[Roger Greenaway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Andy-Williams-Home-Lovin-Man/release/1736879 |title=Andy Williams - Home Lovin' Man (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nMuch of his attention in the early 1970s was diverted by a protracted legal dispute with his [[Music publisher (popular music)|publishers]].<ref name=\"AMG\"/> He won his case on appeal in 1974, in a landmark decision which encouraged other artists to challenge the terms of their contracts.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bubblegum-music.com/britgum |title=British Bubblegum: the Works of Tony Macaulay, Roger Cook and Roger Greenaway &#124; Bubblegum University |publisher=Bubblegum-music.com |date=2006-05-04 |accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>  By this time he had begun to turn his back on writing pop songs and started to write for musical theatre. His first collaborations for the [[theatre|stage]] were with the [[playwright]] [[Ken Hill (playwright)|Ken Hill]] on ''Is Your Doctor Really Necessary?'' in 1973, and on ''Gentlemen Prefer Anything'' the following year.<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nHe composed the scores to the films ''[[The Beast in the Cellar]]'' (1970) and ''[[Percy's Progress]]'' (1974), and was the music co-ordinator for the [[film]] ''Never Too Young to Rock'' (1975). He also wrote the music for ''[[Windy City (musical)|Windy City]]'', a musical in two acts based on ''[[The Front Page]]'' by [[Ben Hecht]] and [[Charles MacArthur]], with book and [[lyrics]] by [[Dick Vosburgh]], which was premiered on stage in 1982.<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nLater Macaulay turned to writing [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |title=Official Website |publisher=Tony Macaulay |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222112549/http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |archivedate=22 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tonymacaulay.com/ Official website]\n\n{{The Foundations}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macaulay, Tony}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:English composers]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:English thriller writers]]\n[[Category:People from Fulham]]\n[[Category:The Foundations]]\n[[Category:Jewish songwriters]]\n[[Category:English people of German-Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the English writer and composer|the Northern Irish writer, management consultant and peace builder|Tony Macaulay (writer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image               = \n| name                = Tony Macaulay\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = Anthony Gordon Instone\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1944|4|21}}\n| origin              = [[Fulham]], London, England\n| genre               = \n| occupation          = [[Record producer]]<br/>[[Composer]]<br/>[[Songwriter]]<br/>[[Author]]\n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = [http://www.tonymacaulay.com/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''Tony Macaulay''' (born '''Anthony Gordon Instone''', 21 April 1944, England)<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|last=Eder |first=Bruce |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/tony-macaulay-mn0000009429 |title=Tony Macaulay - Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date=1944-04-21 |accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> is an [[English people|English]] [[author]], [[composer]] for [[musical theatre]], and [[songwriter]]. He has won the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors]] Award twice as 'Songwriter of the Year' (1970 and 1977).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |title=Official Website |publisher=Tony Macaulay |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222112549/http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |archivedate=22 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He is a nine time [[Ivor Novello Awards]] winning songwriter. In 2007, he became the only British person to win the Edwin Forrest Award for outstanding contribution to the American theatre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |title=Official Website |publisher=Tony Macaulay |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222112549/http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |archivedate=22 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMacaulay's best-known songs include \"[[Baby Now That I've Found You]]\" and \"[[Build Me Up Buttercup]]\" with [[The Foundations]], \"[[(Last Night) I Didn't Get to Sleep at All]],\" as well as \"[[Love Grows (Where My Rosemary Goes)]]\" and \"[[Don't Give Up on Us (song)|Don't Give Up on Us]]\".\n\n==Career==\nMacaulay was born in [[Fulham]], London, England.<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nIn the early 1960s he worked as a [[song plugger]] for [[Howie Richmond|Essex Publishing]], then moved to [[Pye Records]] as a [[record producer]].<ref name=\"AMG\"/>  It was here that he had his first major success with [[The Foundations]], when they [[sound recording and reproduction|recorded]], \"[[Baby Now That I've Found You]]\", a [[song]] he had co-written with [[John Macleod (songwriter)|John Macleod]], and it topped the [[UK Singles Chart]] in November 1967.<ref name=\"AMG\"/><ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 209}}</ref>  \n\nFurther [[hit single|hits]] came with songs such as [[Marmalade (band)|Marmalade]]'s \"[[Baby Make It Soon]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/baby-make-it-soon-mt0003528787 |title=Baby Make It Soon - Marmalade : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and \"Falling Apart at the Seams\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/falling-apart-at-the-seams-mt0001127531 |title=Falling Apart at the Seams - Marmalade : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[The 5th Dimension]]'s \"[[(Last Night) I Didn't Get to Sleep at All]]\",<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenwald |first=Matthew |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/last-night-i-didnt-get-to-sleep-at-all-mt0013274873 |title=(Last Night) I Didn't Get to Sleep at All - The 5th Dimension : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[David Soul]]'s \"[[Don't Give Up on Us (song)|Don't Give Up on Us]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/David-Soul-Dont-Give-Up-On-Us-Black-Bean-Soup/release/1339153 |title=David Soul - Don't Give Up On Us / Black Bean Soup (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> plus [[Donna Summer]]'s 1977 [[single (music)|single]] \"[[Can't We Just Sit Down (And Talk It Over)]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Donna-Summer-Cant-We-Just-Sit-Down-And-Talk-It-Over-I-Feel-Love/release/53270 |title=Donna Summer - Can't We Just Sit Down (And Talk It Over) / I Feel Love (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> each of which he wrote on his own. Many others came in collaboration with other songwriters, amongst them were [[Long John Baldry]]'s \"[[Let the Heartaches Begin]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/let-the-heartaches-begin-mt0000849004 |title=Let the Heartaches Begin - Long John Baldry : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[Paper Dolls (band)|Paper Dolls]]' \"[[Something Here in My Heart (Keeps A Tellin' Me No)]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/something-here-in-my-heart-keeps-a-tellin-me-no-mt0013029607 |title=Something Here in My Heart (Keeps A-Tellin' Me No) - Paper Dolls : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and [[Pickettywitch]]'s \"[[That Same Old Feeling]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/that-same-old-feeling-mt0026811380 |title=That Same Old Feeling - Pickettywitch : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> all co-written with John Macleod.  Another success for The Foundations was \"[[Build Me Up Buttercup]]\", written by Macaulay and [[Mike D'Abo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/build-me-up-buttercup-mt0011268256 |title=Build Me Up Buttercup - The Foundations : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]]'s \"[[Lights of Cincinnati]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Scott-Walker-Lights-Of-Cincinnati/release/1207970 |title=Scott Walker - Lights Of Cincinnati (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> [[The Hollies]]' \"[[Sorry Suzanne]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/sorry-suzanne-mt0000010583 |title=Sorry Suzanne - The Hollies : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> [[The New Seekers]]' \"[[You Won't Find Another Fool Like Me]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/you-wont-find-another-fool-like-me-mt0001007944 |title=You Won't Find Another Fool Like Me - The New Seekers : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref><ref name=\"AMG\"/> were penned with [[Geoff Stephens]]; whilst [[Edison Lighthouse]]'s \"[[Love Grows (Where My Rosemary Goes)]]\", was written with Sylvan Whittingham and [[Barry Mason]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/love-grows-where-my-rosemary-goes-mt0011983238 |title=Love Grows (Where My Rosemary Goes) - Edison Lighthouse : Listen, Appearances, Song Review |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>  In addition, he co-wrote [[Johnny Johnson and the Bandwagon]]'s \"Blame It On The Pony Express\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Johnny-Johnson-And-His-Bandwagon-Blame-It-On-The-Pony-Express/release/3449134 |title=Johnny Johnson And His Bandwagon* - (Blame It) On The Pony Express (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> and [[Andy Williams]]' \"[[Home Lovin' Man]]\", with [[Roger Cook (songwriter)|Roger Cook]] and [[Roger Greenaway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Andy-Williams-Home-Lovin-Man/release/1736879 |title=Andy Williams - Home Lovin' Man (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nMuch of his attention in the early 1970s was diverted by a protracted legal dispute with his [[Music publisher (popular music)|publishers]].<ref name=\"AMG\"/> He won his case on appeal in 1974, in a landmark decision which encouraged other artists to challenge the terms of their contracts.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bubblegum-music.com/britgum |title=British Bubblegum: the Works of Tony Macaulay, Roger Cook and Roger Greenaway &#124; Bubblegum University |publisher=Bubblegum-music.com |date=2006-05-04 |accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>  By this time he had begun to turn his back on writing pop songs and started to write for musical theatre. His first collaborations for the [[theatre|stage]] were with the [[playwright]] [[Ken Hill (playwright)|Ken Hill]] on ''Is Your Doctor Really Necessary?'' in 1973, and on ''Gentlemen Prefer Anything'' the following year.<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nHe composed the scores to the films ''[[The Beast in the Cellar]]'' (1970) and ''[[Percy's Progress]]'' (1974), and was the music co-ordinator for the [[film]] ''Never Too Young to Rock'' (1975). He also wrote the music for ''[[Windy City (musical)|Windy City]]'', a musical in two acts based on ''[[The Front Page]]'' by [[Ben Hecht]] and [[Charles MacArthur]], with book and [[lyrics]] by [[Dick Vosburgh]], which was premiered on stage in 1982.<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\nLater Macaulay turned to writing [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |title=Official Website |publisher=Tony Macaulay |date=2011-01-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222112549/http://www.tonymacaulay.com/biography.htm |archivedate=22 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tonymacaulay.com/ Official website]\n\n{{The Foundations}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macaulay, Tony}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:English composers]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:English thriller writers]]\n[[Category:People from Fulham]]\n[[Category:The Foundations]]\n[[Category:Jewish songwriters]]\n[[Category:English people of German-Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "bring intro into line with bio standards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Macaulay"}
